setup¶

Note: Before running this notebook, populate the database:

$ python3 repopulate_db.py

All API endpoints that modify the database (rather than just fetching data from it) take a test argument, and if test is False, no changes to the database are made. All calls here will use the test parameter.

import os
from pprint import pprint

In [2]:
BASE_URL = 'http://localhost:5000/'
In [3]:
def call_endpoint(method, endpoint,
                  auth=None, verbose=True, return_json=True, **kwargs):
    """
    Args:
        method ({'GET', 'PUT', 'POST', 'DELETE'})
        endpoint (str)
        auth (Tuple[str, str])
        verbose (bool)
        return_json (bool)
        **kwargs
    
    Returns:
        ``requests.response`` or JSON
    """
    url = BASE_URL + endpoint
    response = requests.request(method, url, auth=auth, **kwargs)

    if verbose is True:
        print(method, '=>', response.url)
    if return_json is True:
        return response.json()
    else:
        return response


def get_auth_token(email, password):
    return (call_endpoint('authtoken', 'get', (email, password))['token'], '')

USERS¶

register a new user¶

input: user name, email and password

output: user info with id and created_at fields filled in by the database

In [5]:
user_info = {'name': 'Burton DeWilde',
             'email': 'burtdewilde@gmail.com',
             'password': 'password'}

call_endpoint('POST', 'register',
              json=user_info, params={'test': True})

POST => http://localhost:5000/register?test=True
Out[5]:
{'created_at': None,
 'email': 'burtdewilde@gmail.com',
 'id': None,
 'name': 'Burton DeWilde'}

confirm a newly-registered user¶

input: token generated in the /register endpoint and sent via email

output: nothing

This isn't an endpoint devs actually call, but a GET request is made to it whenever a user clicks on the link in that confirmation email.

authenticate an existing user¶

input: user email and password

output: authentication token, expires in 30 minutes

get user's info by id¶

input: user id

output: user info, or a subset specified by the fields parameter (note: id is always returned)

In [7]:
call_endpoint('GET', 'users/{id}'.format(id=2), auth=auth)

GET => http://localhost:5000/users/2
Out[7]:
{'created_at': '2016-10-10T21:52:11.353481+00:00',
 'email': 'burtondewilde@gmail.com',
 'id': 2,
 'name': 'Burton DeWilde'}
In [8]:
call_endpoint('GET', 'users/{id}'.format(id=2), auth=auth,
              params={'fields': 'email,name'})

GET => http://localhost:5000/users/2?fields=email%2Cname
Out[8]:
{'email': 'burtondewilde@gmail.com', 'id': 2, 'name': 'Burton DeWilde'}

if you don't know the user's id

intput: user email

output: user info, or a subset

 'email': 'burtondewilde@gmail.com',

delete a user¶

input: user id

output: nothing

note: this also deletes all reviews owned by user, so be very careful

In [10]:
call_endpoint('DELETE', 'users/{id}'.format(id=2), auth=auth,
              params={'test': True})

DELETE => http://localhost:5000/users/2?test=True

CITATIONS¶

create a single citation¶

user manually inputs citation information, one at a time; useful for "gray literature", where a proper RIS or BibTex file isn't readily available

input: citation's information, bare minimum is review id but that's a low bar to pass

output: saved citation info, with id, created_at, and status filled in by the database

In [23]:
citation_to_add = {
    'review_id': 1,
    'title': 'My Great Citation',
    'authors': 'B. DeWilde',
    }

call_endpoint('POST', 'citations', auth=auth,
              json=citation_to_add,
              params={'test': True})

POST => http://localhost:5000/citations?test=True

upload many citations in a file¶

input: review id and full path on disk of citations file to upload

output: nothing

filepaths = ['../colandr_data/citations/ci-full-collection-group1.ris',
             '../colandr_data/citations/ci-full-collection-group2.ris']

for filepath in filepaths:
    filename = os.path.split(filepath)[-1]
    call_endpoint('POST', 'citations/upload', auth=auth,
                  data={'review_id': 1, 'test': True},
                  files={'uploaded_file': (filename, io.open(filepath, mode='rb'))})

Screen Citations¶

submit a screening¶

input: citation id (in URL), status, and (if excluded) list of exclude reasons

output: citation screening info, plus id, created_at, review_id, and user_id fields filled in by the database

In [29]:
citation_id = 1
screening_1 = {'status': 'included'}
screening_2 = {'status': 'excluded', 'exclude_reasons': ['foo', 'bar']}

result_1 = call_endpoint(
    'POST', 'citations/{}/screenings'.format(citation_id),
    json=screening_1, params={'test': True},
    auth=('caugustin@rsmas.miami.edu', 'password'))

pprint(result_1)
print()

result_2 = call_endpoint(
    'POST', 'citations/{}/screenings'.format(citation_id),
    json=screening_2, params={'test': True},
    auth=('rcm2164@columbia.edu', 'password'))

pprint(result_2)

FULLTEXTS¶

fulltexts are created automatically when a citation is marked as "included", and removed automatically when a citation is un-marked as "included" (which is actually more of an edge case). the api endpoints are mostly analogous to those for citations.

get a single fulltext¶

input: fulltext id, fields to return (optional)

output: fulltext info; note: this also includes associated citation and screenings, if fields are not specified

In [32]:
fulltext_id = 10

call_endpoint('GET', 'fulltexts/{id}'.format(id=fulltext_id),
              params={'fields': None},
              auth=auth)

GET => http://localhost:5000/fulltexts/10

Environmental Evidence 2014, 3:16\nhttp://www.environmentalevidencejournal.org/content/3/1/16SYSTEMATIC REVIEW PROTOCOL Open AccessWhat are the impacts of nature conservation\ninterventions on human well-being: a systematic\nmap protocol\nMadeleine Bottrill1*, Samantha Cheng2, Ruth Garside3, Supin Wongbusarakum4, Dilys Roe5, Margaret B Holland6,\nJanet Edmond1 and Will R Turner1Abstract\nBackground: International policy has sought to emphasize and strengthen the link between the conservation of\nnatural ecosystems and human development. Furthermore, international conservation organizations have broadened\ntheir objectives beyond nature-based goals to recognize the contribution of conservation interventions in sustaining\necosystem services upon which human populations are dependent. While many indices have been developed to\nmeasure various human well-being domains, the strength of evidence to support the effects, both positive and\nnegative, of conservation interventions on human well-being, is still unclear.\nMethods/Design: This protocol describes the methodology for examining the research question: What are the impacts\nof nature conservation interventions on different domains of human well-being in developing countries? Using systematic\nmapping, this study will scope and identify studies that measure the impacts of nature conservation interventions on\nhuman well-being at local to regional scales. The primary objective of this study is to synthesize the state and distribution\nof the existing evidence base linking conservation and human well-being. In addition, a theory of change approach will\nbe used to identify and characterize the causal linkages between conservation and human well-being, with attention on\nthose studies that examine the role of ecosystem services. Key trends among the resulting studies will be synthesized\nand the range of studies organized and presented in a graphical matrix illustrating the relationships between types\nof interventions and types of outcomes. Results of the study are intended to help conservation and development\npractitioners and the academic community to improve research studies and conservation practices in developing\ncountries in order to achieve both conservation and human well-being outcomes.\nKeywords: Conservation, Ecosystem services, Human Well-being, PovertyBackground\nThe World Conservation Strategy, published by the\nInternational Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN),\nthe United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and\nWorld Wildlife Fund (WWF) in 1980 [1] was the first\nkey international policy program to strengthen the links\nbetween nature conservation and human development\n[2]. Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, conservation and\ndevelopment organizations promoted and implemented a\nlarge number of initiatives aimed at enhancing the benefits\nof nature conservation for populations at both local and* Correspondence: mbottrill@conservation.org\n1Conservation International, 2011 Crystal Drive, Suite 500, Arlington, VA\n22202, USA\nFull list of author information is available at the end of the article\n© 2014 Bottrill et al.; licensee BioMed Central\nCommons Attribution License (http://creativec\nreproduction in any medium, provided the or\nDedication waiver (http://creativecommons.or\nunless otherwise stated.wider scales. These have taken the form of integrated con-\nservation and development projects, community-based\nnatural resource management, community conservation\nand so on. The 1980s also witnessed an increased focus\non human rights within the conservation movement,\nparticularly on indigenous rights and community dis-\nplacement from protected areas. As early as 1975, the\nIUCN General Assembly adopted a Recommendation\nthat indigenous peoples\' rights should be taken into\naccount in national parks and other protected areas and\nthis was reaffirmed at the 1982 World Parks Congress and\nat subsequent IUCN meetings [3].\nThis attention to the human dimensions of conservation\nhas increased significantly since the turn of the new mil-\nlennium. These links\ninclude essential ecosystem services such as water\npurification, fisheries, and pollination that underpin\nhuman health, contribute to food security, and support\nlivelihoods.\nIn parallel to policy shifts, increasingly, several major\ninternational conservation organizations, including Birdlife\nInternational, Conservation International, The Nature\nConservancy and Fauna & Flora International explicitly\nreference people in their mission and vision statements\nand aspire to achieve socially beneficial outcomes from\ntheir conservation efforts [9,10]. Conservation International\n(CI) specifically revised its mission in 2007 in order to\nsupport human well-being by restoring and protecting\necosystems that provide essential goods and services.\nRecently, guidance to address social results and human\nwell-being targets and outcomes in conservation projects\nhas been developed (e.g., [11-13]).\nThis evolution towards a greater emphasis on the\nhuman dimensions of conservation efforts has occurred\nfor a number of reasons. Over the years, conservation\nhas been portrayed as both a win-win solution for\npoverty alleviation and sustainable development, and as\na constraint on economic growth [14]. While several\nconservation projects have achieved both conservation\nand development goals [15-17], conflicts and negative\nrelationships between conservation and human well-\nbeing have also been highlighted [18], including loss of\naccess rights [19], human-wildlife conflict [20], and –\nmost controversially – evictions from protected areas\n[21]. Thus, conservation policy has been dually influenced\nby a need to demonstrate contributions to broader devel-\nopment goals (e.g., USAID\'s Biodiversity Policy 2014,\n[22]) as well as a genuine desire to secure and ensure the\nlongevity of natural ecosystems upon which vulnerable\npopulations depend [23].\nUnderlying this increasing focus on the human dimen-\nsions of conservation, several predominant hypotheses exist\nabout the explicit effects of conservation interventions on\nboth the tangible (e.g. economic and material wealth,\nphysical and psychological health) to the intangible (e.g.,\nsocial cohesion, culture, equity and good governance)\ndomains of human well-being (Figure 1). These domains of\nhuman well-being are often interdependent and mutually\nreinforcing. For example, the presence of tangible well-\nbeing benefits such as secure jobs and good individualphysical health can influence household and community\nwell-being, while good governance can result in security\nand access to livelihood resources that in turn enhance\neconomic wellbeing [24,25].\nWhile many indices have been developed to document or\nmeasure various human well-being domains of conserva-\ntion interventions [9,23,26], these have not been associated\nwith approaches or tools for critically assessing the strength\nof these relationships, nor the consequences of these out-\nputs on management decisions. With an increasing focus\non human dimensions of conservation, decisions are neces-\nsary about what interventions are effective at meeting social\nand biophysical objectives, which indicators are the right\nones to measure progress, how and when changes are ex-\npected to occur, and what evidence is available to support\nthese decisions. Yet the state of current evidence or in-\nformation from relevant and rigorous research, docu-\nmenting the impacts of nature conservation on human\nwell-being is unclear. For example, while it is widely recog-\nnized both in literature and emergent policy that ecosys-\ntem services are a vital component of environmental\nprovision for human well-being (Figure 1), many ques-\ntions still remain around the specific role they play and\nthe causal relationships between services and out-\ncomes [27]. As illustrated for direct payment schemes,\nfor example (Figure 2), conservation interventions might\naffect human well-being through direct provision of in-\ncome from payments that then facilitate better livelihoods,\nbut also in directing through ecosystem services. For ex-\nample, payments might promote advocacy for conserving\nnatural ecosystems which lead to human well-being bene-\nfits such as by sustaining wild food sources and nature-\nbased livelihoods. Negative, unintended, consequences\nmight also emerge from the flow of new income\nsources into communities, as well as issues of equity.\nSeveral issues affect the ability of the conservation\nsector to adequately assess contributions to human well-\nbeing. First, the interactions and dependencies between\nnatural and social systems have yet to be sufficiently inte-\ngrated into existing assessment frameworks, which are\nmainly focused on either ecological or socio-economic\nbenefits. Second, empirical evidence demonstrating links\nbetween healthy ecosystems and human well-being is still\nlacking, with reporting and evaluation of conservation\noutcomes limited and inconsistent. Consequently, in the\nabsence of a coherent evidence base about what works,\nand what does not, conservation organizations and their\npartners are continuing to implement interventions under\nassumptions about likely effects. This uncertainty brings\nconsiderable risk, as investments could fail to achieve\none or both ecological and social objectives, waste\nscarce available resources, and damage the credibility of\nconservation efforts with donors, decision makers, and\nother stakeholders.\nFigure 2 Detailed conceptual model illustrating theory of change linking direct payments for conservation with intended outcomes for\nhuman well-being through multiple causal pathways.\nFigure 1 Conceptual model illustrating direct and indirect relationships between nature conservation interventions and human\nwell-being outcomes.\nBottrill et al. Environmental Evidence 2014, 3:16 Page 4 of 11\nhttp://www.environmentalevidencejournal.org/content/3/1/16Recent studies have begun to characterize evidence\non the relationships between nature and people. These\nefforts have related to specific types of conservation\ninterventions (e.g., protected areas, [28]; community\nforest management, [29]), alternative livelihood schemes\n[30], payments for ecosystem services [31]; and eco-\ncertification, [32]; and specific components of biodiversity\n[33]. Work has also been done to formulate frameworks\nfor analyzing the impacts and causal pathways of specific\nconservation projects on both natural and social outcomes\n[34,35]. Recent advances are encouraging, yet existing\nstudies have taken a more narrow focus to examining\nlinkages between conservation and human well-being,\nlooking at one specific type of intervention on a specific\ntype of outcome limiting insight into interdependent\ncontexts and outcomes [27,36] and the broader landscape\non which conservation outcomes play out. In contrast,\nour study aims to examine the impact of different types of\ninterventions upon a wide range of possible outcomes and\ncausal pathways. Benefits of a larger review therefore\ninclude: 1) avoiding assumptions about effects of widely\napplied interventions; 2) inclusion of non-traditional or\nlesser known interventions and dimensions of well-being;\nand 3) generalizability to decision making across the\noverall sector.\nTo address this question, we use systematic mapping\nas a tool for describing the breadth and current state\nof the evidence base with an aim to characterize and\nvisually represent the causal linkages supported by this\nevidence base. Systematic mapping, also known as evidence\ngap mapping [37], is an useful method to thematically\nsynthesize and characterize, or "map", collections of evi-\ndence, particularly to provide basis for policy decisions\n[38]. This technique allows identification of weak or\nlacking evidence on key linkages which might facilitate\npolicy-making decisions based existing knowledge in\norder to direct resources most effectively. The outputs\nof such mapping include structured matrices depicting\nthe distribution and frequency of studies, and coding\nfor study design or mechanism type, across a range of\ninterventions and outcome variables. Beyond character-\nizing the existing evidence base, we will apply theory of\nchange conceptual modelling methods [39,40] to define\ncategories for organizing data (e.g., intermediate and\nlong-term outcomes), and to interpret prevalent direct\nand indirect causal pathways between conservation inter-\nventions and human well-being outcomes.\nAims and objectives of the systematic map\nThis mapping exercise will scope and identify studies\nthat document and/or measure the impacts of nature\nconservation interventions on human well-being at local\nto regional scales. The emphasis will be on direct effects to\ndiscrete populations, beneficiaries or targeted stakeholders,with a focus on households, communities, or individuals in\ndeveloping countries, as these populations are likely to be\nmost dependent on nature and/or most sensitive to positive\nor negative impacts of conservation.\nThe primary research question is:\nWhat are the impacts of nature conservation\ninterventions on different domains of human\nwell-being in developing countries?\nThe systematic map will synthesize an index of literature\nand map the evidence illustrating the breadth of causal\nlinkages between both positive and negative effects of\nnature conservation and human well-being (Table 1).\nThe primary objective of the systematic map is to assess\nand characterize the current state and distribution of\nthe existing evidence base. The map is focused on evidence\nrelated to effects of nature conservation which includes\ninterventions primarily intended to achieve protection and\nmanagement of natural ecosystems in-situ and generally\nexcludes ex-situ interventions such as seed banks cap-\ntive breeding and environmental regulatory measures,\nsuch as control of air pollution, waste management, water\ntreatment or energy production. For our purposes, human\nwell-being is a multi-dimensional concept, encompassing\nboth tangible and intangible effects [41], and defined most\nbroadly as the "the satisfaction of human needs to achieve\na state of being well (i.e., healthy, happy, and prosperous),\nboth physically and mentally" [42]. The evidence base\nwill be explored and characterized using a targeted data\nextraction strategy to answer a set of secondary research\nquestions:\n What is the current state and distribution of\nevidence?\n What types of impacts from conservation\ninterventions on human well-being are measured?\n What types of ecosystem services are explicitly\nassociated with the impacts of conservation\ninterventions on human well-being?\n What populations are affected by conservation and/\nor focus of studies?\n How does the evidence base align with major\npriorities and investments of implementing agencies?\nThis will include identifying the range of conservation\ninterventions linked to different domains of human well-\nbeing, along with geographic location, duration of inter-\nventions, and the types of conservation objectives defined\nby studies.\nGiven the emphasis which contemporary conservation\nstrategies and research place on the role of ecosystem ser-\nvices play in connecting conservation to human well-being,\nthis study will also assess which services are associated with\nTable 1 Key elements of the study research question\nPopulation Intervention Comparator Outcome\nHuman populations, including\nindividuals, households, communities or\nnation states in non-OECD countries\nAdoption or implementation\nof nature conservation\ninterventions\nNo use of nature conservation\ninterventions either between\nsites or groups, or over time\nseries (before/after)\nPositive or negative effects on\nthe multi-dimensional well-being\nstatus of human populations\nBottrill et al. A theory of change is a graphical illustration,\ngenerated in a participatory process, which represents\nhow an intervention is expected to lead to planned out-\ncomes through explicitly identifying causal links between\noutputs, intermediate outcomes and final outcomes\nalong with the critical assumptions underlying those\nlinks [40]. We intend to specifically use theory of change\nin several ways: 1) understand the conceptual basis for\nthe study and the types of pathways by which conserva-\ntion might affect human well-being; 2) design data extrac-\ntion questionnaire, and 3) present and interpret of results\nthrough framework synthesis. Progress on integration\nof theory of change modelling into systematic mapping\ndesign and implementation is explained below.\nIn an expert workshop in November 2013 (Additional\nfile 1), hosted by Conservation International, theory of\nchange methods were used to support development of\nquestions for data extraction, understand prevalent path-\nways between conservation action and well-being out-\ncomes,. In addition, participants articulated a high-level\ntheory of change for the research question (see Figure 1).\nThe role of causal mechanisms and pathways were further\nexplored for specific interventions (example shown in\nFigure 2). Explicit consideration of the program theory,\ne.g., how the intervention is expected to lead to planned\noutcomes, will help the project team to identify relevant\nquestions and test a priori hypotheses prominently used\nin the sector [43]. With a theory of change model,\nassumptions about the attribution of project strategies\nand activities to changes in human well-being can be\narticulated and rival explanations taken into consider-\nation. We will pilot question(s) relating to identification\nof types of mechanisms as part of the data extraction.\nWe are wary to attempt to articulate anticipated pathways\nor mechanisms by which This process will ex-\npedite review of grey literature, which might have more\ngeneral titles or lack abstracts.\nComprehensiveness of search\nThe search strategy for our systematic map is largely\ndependent on conservation literature available on online\npublication databases. The two databases, Scopus and\nWeb of Science, list articles from major conservation,\nenvironment, and development journals. The online\ndatabase is limited to articles published in these journals\nfrom 1980 onwards and therefore the search will not\ncapture articles published earlier. To expand the search\nfor relevant evidence, a search of grey literature will be\nconducted. To ensure\ncomprehensiveness of the search, alternate terms for\nintervention and outcome variables have been tested\nusing a test library (Additional file 2) and disaggregated\nusing wild cards and other variations on similar words.\nLimitations to the comprehensiveness of the search\ninclude consideration of only English language publications\ndue to time and resource constraints. Further limitations\ninclude access to grey literature and time required to\ncollate studies from availability of studies by developing\ncountry researchers due to biases associated with peer-\nreviewed publications and the same aforementioned\nlanguage constraints.\nInclusion and exclusion criteria\nFollowing compilation of database hits based on the\nsearch string and the removal of duplicates, the articles\ncaptured will be screened against a series of inclusion\nand exclusion criteria (first applied to titles and then to\nabstracts). Reported studies will be included in the map\nif they meet the following criteria:\nRelevant population\n The study focuses on the well-being of individuals,\nhouseholds or communities, or nation states living\nin non-OECD countries.Relevant intervention\n The study involves establishment, adoption, or\nimplementation of an intervention that regulates,\nprotects or manages biodiversity and natural\necosystems through in-situ activities.\nRelevant outcomes\n The study describes effects on one or more domains\nof human well-being categorized as follows: Living\nstandards (Material, Economic), Health, Education,\nSecurity/Safety, Social Wellness, Equity, Spiritual and\nCultural Fulfillment, Psychological/Mental Well-\nbeing, Governance, and Resource Rights and Access.\nRelevant study designs\n All study designs will be included if they measure the\neffect of a conservation intervention including impact\nevaluations, econometrics analyses, case studies, and\nobservational studies. Secondary studies, e.g.,\nsystematic reviews and meta-analyses, will also be\nmarked and set aside as a separate group.\nIrrelevant Population/Subject\n Studies focusing on OECD countries will not be\nincluded;\n Studies without a discrete population such as those\ncommenting on effects of undefined groups or\npopulations will not be included.\nIrrelevant interventions\n Studies that document, measure or observe people\'s\ndaily use or interaction with natural ecosystems\nand/or ecosystem goods or services rather than\nassociated with a specific and discrete external\nintervention will not be included;\n Studies focused on environmental regulatory measures\nand mitigation (air quality control, waste management,\nenergy production) and ex-situ conservation efforts\n(e.g., zoos, captive breeding and seed banks).\nIrrelevant outcome\n Studies that do not measure or describe human\nwell-being outcomes or studies that only focus on\nbiophysical outcomes of conservation.\nIrrelevant types of studies\n Theoretical studies or models\nBottrill et al. Environmental Evidence 2014, 3:16 Page 9 of 11\nhttp://www.environmentalevidencejournal.org/content/3/1/16 Studies where population or subject is not\ndefined – e.g., global public good.\n Studies that explore the effect of human well-being\non biophysical conservation outcomes\nScreening\nFollowing implementation of the search strategy, all titles\nwill be reviewed. Abstracts of articles with relevant titles\nfrom the first stage will be assessed against the inclusion\nand exclusion criteria above. The title and abstract review\nstages will be conducted by two researchers, who will scan\nstudies based upon the criteria. If there is any doubt about\nthe relevance of an article, it will be retained for full text\nassessment. The reviewers will perform a title and abstract\nscreening of a similar random subset of reference list (up\nto 1000 references) in a pilot exercise to assess repeatabil-\nity of the selection criteria. Articles retained following the\ntitle and abstract review stages will have a full-text assess-\nment based upon the inclusion and exclusion criteria. The\nfull-text assessment will take place during the process of\ndata extraction as detailed in the following sections.\nData extraction strategy\nEach article in the full-text assessment will be examined\nusing a standard questionnaire and supplementary code-\nbook (Additional file 5: Conservation-Human Well-Being\nLinkages Assessment) for categorizing the data generated\nfrom the data extraction strategy. The questionnaire was\ndeveloped to capture key descriptive information about\nthe article and framed according to the research questions\nrelevant to this study. The questionnaire was reviewed\nand refined based upon feedback gathered during the\nNovember 2013 expert workshop. A form for extracting\ndata will be developed in Google Forms, which will then\nautomatically compile extracted data into a spreadsheet.\nThe following broad categories of data will be extracted:\n1. Bibliographic information\n2. Basic information about type of conservation\nintervention\n3. Basic information on study design and subjects\n4. Human well-being outcomes\n5. Outcome pathways and mechanisms affecting\nchange\nCategories for describing intervention type and out-\ncomes have been identified a priori and compiled into a\nstructured matrix. To develop appropriate questions to\nfirst identify mechanisms, and then characterize them,\nwe will conduct a pilot with a subset of studies. Some\npotential constraints in characterizing mechanisms, include\nthe sheer size of the systematic mapping exercise, is our\nhesitancy to attempt to interpret assumed relationships\nwithin a study without conceptual model or logicalframework present, and potential to include all internal and\nexternal factors that might affect conservation success ver-\nsus causal mechanism(s) assumed to link conservation ac-\ntion to changes in well-being.\nStudy quality assessment\nGiven the scope of the mapping process, we do not plan\nto assess the quality of included studies. By their nature,\nsystematic maps, or evidence gap maps, are broad in\nscope and limited in depth in order to explore the charac-\nteristics of the evidence base rather than specific issues on\nquality and strength [37]. As part of the data extraction\nstrategy, we will collate data on study design where\npossible and on what type of comparators are used\n(see further details in data extraction questionnaire in\nAdditional file 5). Information on study design will be\ncollected, e.g., type of data collected, sample size, duration\nof study, and used as a proxy to the frequency of study\ndesign types, and their relative rigor, among different\nstudies which might indicate quality of the study design.\nWe will however be cautious not to assert that type or fre-\nquency of study design as a substitute for confidence in\nthe effects of specific interventions.\nData mapping and presentation\nA key output of mapping existing evidence will be a\nstructured matrix, which is a graphical illustration of\nthe distribution and frequencies of studies to document\nspecific relationships between a range of interventions\nand outcomes [37]. Evidence on different outcomes (in\ncolumns) is mapped onto different categories of inter-\nventions (in rows). Each cell represents a study. Each\ncell can be color-coded according to different criteria,\ne.g., types of study design, geographic location etc. The\nstructured matrix will be developed using framework\nsynthesis, which applies pre-determined categories to\nthe data and enables structured comparison [47]. Extrac-\ntion of data from individual studies will be organized\nbased upon the structured matrix. A draft matrix is\navailable in Additional file 6 which illustrates the range\nof interventions and outcomes. Using software under\ndevelopment by the International Impact Initiative (3ie),\nwe intend to produce an online version of the gap map,\nwhich will enable each cell to be linked to a user-friendly\nsummary of each study to allow the user to explore the\nmain findings and other information on each study in\nmore detail. Alternatively to the 3ie online system, we will\nalso explore other knowledge management tools such as\nEarthcube (http://earthcube.ning.com/).\nIn addition to the structured matrix, all articles included\nin the full text assessment will be characterized using\ndescriptive statistics on key trends, including:\n Type of conservation interventions\nBottrill et al. Environmental Evidence 2014, 3:16 Page 10 of 11\nhttp://www.environmentalevidencejournal.org/content/3/1/16 Human well-being outcomes\n Type of study design\n Direction of impact\n Type of causal mechanism\nGeographic locations and ecosystem types will be\nspatially mapped where discrete study locations are\navailable. Given the size of the study, detailed analysis\ninto the type and frequency of mechanisms influencing\ncausal pathways will be limited. Where conceptual model\nor logical frameworks are explicit in a study, we will\nattempt to characterize the range of mechanisms doc-\numented and colour code studies in the structured\nmatrix for each type of mechanism linking a specific\nintervention to a specific outcome.\nAdditional files\nAdditional file 1: CI expert workshop and list of participants.\nAdditional file 2: List of publications in test library.\nAdditional file 3: Scoping of search terms and evolution of search\nstring.xls.\nAdditional file 4: Comparison on Scopus subject areas and Web of\nScience research areas.\nAdditional file 5: Conservation-Human Well-being Linkages\nAssessment.xls.\nAdditional file 6: Template for structured matrix.\nCompeting interests\nThe authors declare that they have no conflicts of interest.\nAuthors\' contributions\nMB jointly with WT conceived the study and secured the funding support.\nMB and SC co-wrote the manuscript. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 2 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5Background\nThe problem: lack of precision in systematic searches\nSystematic reviews are a widely used method to bring\ntogether the findings from multiple studies in a reliable\nway and are often used to inform policy and practice,\nsuch as guideline development [1,2]. Whilst they are\noften associated with medical research and randomised\ncontrolled trials, they can be used to address any re-\nsearch question using any relevant type of research [3].\nA critical feature of a systematic review is the application\nof scientific methods to uncover and minimise bias and\nerror in the selection and treatment of studies [4,5].\nHowever, the large and growing number of published\nstudies, and their increasing rate of publication, makes\nthe task of identifying relevant studies in an unbiased\nway both complex and time consuming [6].\nIn order to minimise the impact of publication bias\n[7], reviewers make efforts to identify all relevant re-\nsearch for inclusion in systematic reviews. This has al-\nways been a challenging and time-consuming aspect of\nreviewing, but the challenge is growing due to the in-\ncrease in the number of databases to search and the\nnumber of papers and journals being published; more-\nover, as recent work has suggested that there is an in-\nbuilt North American bias in many major bibliographic\ndatabases (e.g. PubMed), a wide range of smaller databases\nneeds to be searched in order to identify research for re-\nviews that aim to maximise external validity [8]. In prac-\ntice, this means adopting a multi-layered approach to\nsearching which combines: extensive Boolean searches of\nelectronic bibliographic databases, specialised registers\nand websites; with individual approaches to authors and\nkey informants; and the following of \'citation trails\' (iden-\ntifying which papers are cited by a relevant study and\nwhich papers in turn cite the paper that it is reported in)\n[9]. Of these three approaches, searching databases yields\naround three quarters of the studies finally included [10].\nUnfortunately, the specificity of sensitive electronic\nsearches of bibliographic databases is low (for definitions\nof specificity, recall and other key metrics, see Table 1).\nReviewers often need to look manually through many\nthousands of irrelevant titles and abstracts in order to\nidentify the much smaller number of relevant ones [7]; a\nprocess known as screening. Reviews that address com-\nplex health issues or that deal with a range of interven-\ntions (e.g. a typical public health review might be\nconcerned with \'interventions to promote physical ac-\ntivity\') are often those that have the most challenging\nnumbers of items to screen. Given that an experienced\nreviewer can take between 30 seconds and several mi-\nnutes to evaluate a citation [11], the work involved in\nscreening 10,000 citations is considerable (and the\nscreening burden in some reviews is considerably higher\nthan this) (see also [12]).Reviewers are thus faced with two competing demands.\nReviews that are to be used to inform policy and practice\noften need to be completed to externally defined (often\nshort) timetables within limited budgets; but in order for a\nreview to be an accurate reflection of the state of know-\nledge in a given area, it needs to be comprehensive.\nThe need to complete reviews to tight timescales has\nled (particularly in health technology assessments and\nother rapid reviews) to the adoption of highly pragmatic\n(and relatively specific) strategies to searching in order to\nlimit the number of studies to screen—even though rele-\nvant research is probably missed because of this [16].\nLimiting the recall of a search may undermine one of\nthe most important principles of a systematic review:\nthat its results are based on an unbiased set of studies.\nThe key problem—which this paper aims to begin to ad-\ndress—is that there are currently no widely accepted al-\nternative ways of dealing with this issue. Reviews are at\nrisk of either limiting their searches to such a degree\nthat the validity of their findings is questionable or of in-\ncreasing the time and resources they require and thus\nrisk being unable to inform policy and practice.\nProposed \'solution\': the (semi)-automation of screening\nBroadly speaking, text mining is defined as the process\nof discovering knowledge and structure from unstruc-\ntured data (i.e., text) [17,18]. In the context of finding re-\nsearch for inclusion in a review, we are interested in\nautomated techniques of discovering whether a given\nstudy (described by a title and abstract) is relevant to\nour review [19,20]. There are two ways of using text\nmining that are particularly promising for assisting with\nscreening in systematic reviews: one aims to prioritise\nthe list of items for manual screening so that the studies\nat the top of the list are those that are most likely to be\nrelevant; the second method uses the manually assigned\ninclude/exclude categories of studies in order to \'learn\' to\napply such categorisations automatically [19]; whilst the\ntechnologies to perform each may be similar, we separate\nthem here as they are conceptually distinct. The prioritisa-\ntion of relevant items may not appear to reduce workload\n(if all citations are to be screened manually anyway), but\nwhen there are large numbers of studies to screen manu-\nally, identifying most of the relevant ones quickly enables\nsome members of a reviewing team to begin the next\nstages of the review, whilst the remainder of mostly irrele-\nvant citations are screened by other team members. This\nreduces the time from review commencement to comple-\ntion, even if the total workload remains the same.\nBy reducing the burden of screening in reviews, new\nmethodologies using text mining may enable systematic\nreviews to both: be completed more quickly (thus\nmeeting exacting policy and practice timescales and in-\ncreasing their cost efficiency); AND minimise the\nTable 1 Definitions of performance measures reported in the studies\nMeasure # Definition Formula\nRecall (sensitivity) 22 Proportion of correctly identified positives\namongst all real positives\nTP\nTPþFN\nPrecision 18 Proportion of correctly identified\npositives amongst all positives.\nTP\nTPþFN\nF measure 10 Combines precision and recall. In turn, byfacilitating more timely and reliable reviews, this meth-\nodology has the potential to improve decision-making\nacross the health sector and beyond.\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 4 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5The research problem\nWhilst the logic behind applying text mining to the screen-\ning stage of systematic reviews has intuitive appeal, there are\nobvious concerns that might be raised by the systematic re-\nview community [21]. Firstly, there is not a lot of informa-\ntion about text mining written for systematic review\naudiences. The vast majority of papers on this topic are pro-\nduced by computer scientists in journals and conference\nproceedings in the field of medical informatics or artificial\nintelligence. This means that they are not particularly ac-\ncessible to systematic reviewers who need to make decisions\nabout their review processes, both in terms of the level of\ntechnical detail presented in the reports and in the exposure\nsuch papers would have in systematic review communities.\nSecondly, for these technologies to achieve broad up-\ntake, they should be accessible to systematic reviewers\nwithout the need for a computer scientist to write be-\nspoke code or undertake custom processing of text for\nindividual reviews. Specialist advice may be required,\nbut it should be akin to the need for occasional special-\nist statistical advice, rather than being at the level of op-\nerating the text mining tools. Any implementation\nissues need to be identified and resolved before rolling\nsuch technologies out to the intended users.\nThirdly, there are various ways in which workload\ncould be reduced through these technologies (reducing\nnumber needed to screen; text mining as a second\nscreener; increasing the rate (speed) of screening and\nimproving workflow through screening prioritisation).\nHowever, not all technologies allow all types of workload\nreduction to be achieved. In order to make informed de-\ncisions about using such technologies, systematic re-\nviewers need to know which technologies can be used\nfor which workload reduction goal.\nFourthly, systematic reviews are a relatively new area in\nwhich text mining technologies have been applied. Some of\nthe assumptions of text mining technologies in other appli-\ncations do not hold when transferred to the review context.\nFor instance, systematic reviewers generally place strong em-\nphasis on high recall—that is, a desire to identify all the rele-\nvant includable studies—even if that means a vast number of\nirrelevant studies need to be considered to find them. When\napplied in other areas, precision (reducing the number of ir-\nrelevant items) and accuracy (correctly classifying items as\nrelevant or irrelevant) are typically more valued. To be ac-\nceptable to the systematic review community, new technolo-\ngies must address the particular challenges and demands of\nthis context (We should also note at this point that we have\nno guarantee of perfect recall even with current methods, as\nsearch strategies are tailored to the resource available to\nscreen results, and humans are likely to make mistakes dur-\ning their manual sifting through records.).\nFinally, the methods, their relative success and the\nmetrics used to evaluate them have not yet been pulledtogether in a systematic way; this current study aims to\nfill that research gap.\nAims and research questions of the review\nThe primary aim of this review is to gather and present\nthe available research evidence on existing methods for\ntext mining related to the title and abstract screening\nstage in a systematic review, including the performance\nmetrics used to evaluate these technologiesa. The pur-\npose of this is to inform systematic reviewers of the\ncurrent state of text mining methods for use in reducing\nworkload at the screening stage, with a consideration of\nthe potential benefits and challenges when implement-\ning such technologies. Whilst we have explored the\nmore technical aspects of text mining technologies in\nour data extraction, the intended audience of this paper\nare users of the technologies rather than computer sci-\nentists, and so technical issues are largely dealt with at a\nconceptual level.\nFollowing directly from the research problem as delin-\neated above, we looked to answer the following questions:\n1. What is the state of the evidence base related to\nautomating (or semi-automating) the screening stage\n(based on titles and abstracts) of a systematic\nreview? Specifically,\na. What methods are available; and\nb. How has the field developed over time?2. How has the workload reduction issue been evaluated?\nSpecifically,\na. What has been compared, using what research\nstudy designs?\nb. What metrics are available for evaluating the\nperformance of the approaches?\n3. What are the stated purposes of (semi-)automating\nthe screening stage through text mining in terms of\nworkload reduction, what types of methods have\nbeen used to address each purpose, and how\neffective were they?\n4. How, and with what effect, have key contextual\nproblems of applying text mining to systematic\nreview screening been addressed, specifically as\nrelates to the following challenges:\na. The importance of high recall for systematic\nreviews?\nb. The risk of hasty generalisation when training\nfrom a certain pool of known includes and\nexcludes?\nc. The problem of imbalanced datasets, in which\nthere are typically many more excludes than\nincludes?\nd. Applying the technologies to review updates?\n5. What challenges to implementation emerge from\nreviewing the evidence base?\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 5 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5Methods\nWe conducted a systematic review of research papers on\napplications of text mining to assist in identifying rele-\nvant studies for inclusion in a systematic review. The\nprotocol can be sent on request by the authors.\nInformation management\nAll records of research identified by searches were\nuploaded to the specialist systematic review software,\nEPPI-Reviewer 4, for duplicate stripping and screening\n[22]. This software recorded the bibliographic details of\neach study considered by the review, where studies were\nfound and how, reasons for their inclusion or exclusion,\ndescriptive and evaluative codes and text about each in-\ncluded study, and the data used and produced during\nsynthesis.\nSearch methods\nDatabase and website searches were conducted in\nDecember 2013. Sources were searched from 2005 on-\nwards. This date was chosen because, according to\nJonnalagadda and Petitti [23], the first proposed applica-\ntion of text mining to screening in systematic reviews\nwas in 2005 (though this was not an evaluation of a\nmethod and so was not included in our review).\nDetails of the electronic search strategy, including data-\nbases searched and terms used, can be found in Additional\nfile 1: Appendix A; the PRISMA flow diagram can be\nviewed in Additional file 2: Flow diagram.\nWe also included papers known to the team and as\nrecommended by colleagues. We checked the reference\nlists of all included studies for additional relevant stud-\nies. We also followed forward citation recommendations\nin Science Direct. A cut-off for identifying studies for in-\nclusion in the review was set at 28 February 2014.\nAfter all searches were completed, 1,253 records were\nidentified. These were screened for relevance to our re-\nview using the inclusion criteria outlined below.\nInclusion criteria\nStudies were screened in a two-stage screening process.\nFirst, records were assessed against the following criteria\nbased on their titles and abstracts:\n1. Must be published after 2004\n2. Must be relevant to text mining\n3. Must be relevant to the screening (document\nselection) stage of a systematic review (or a review\nof the evidence that follows systematic principles,\nsuch as health technology assessment (HTA) or\nguidelines development)\nAfter an initial piloting of the first stage criteria to es-\ntablish common understanding of the criteria, recordswere screened once by two researchers (AOM and JT)\nwho are familiar with systematic reviewing and text min-\ning methods. Any records of doubtful relevance were\nmarked with a \'query\' tag and discussed by the two re-\nsearchers until agreement was met (Agreement was al-\nways reached, and so recourse to a third reviewer was\nnot required.).\nThe full-text documents of records that met these cri-\nteria (n = 69) were retrieved and proceeded to the sec-\nond stage of screening. The criteria for assessing the\nfull-text documents were:\n1. Must be relevant to text mining methods or metrics\n2. Must be relevant to the screening stage of a\nsystematic review (or similar evidence review)\n3. Must not be a general discussion of the use of text\nmining in systematic reviewing screening. That is,\nthe record must present a detailed method or\nevaluation of a method.\nThe second stage of screening was conducted by one\nresearcher (AOM), with queried records checked by the\nsecond researcher (JT) (reviewer agreement was 100% at\nthis stage). After full-text screening, a total of 44 records\nwere identified as relevant to the review questions.\nData extraction\nData extraction was conducted by one researcher\n(AOM) and checked for accuracy and completeness by a\nsecond researcher (JT) and discrepancies resolved by a\nsecond check and/or discussion. We extracted and re-\ncorded information on the following broad issues (see\nAdditional file 1: Appendix B for the full data extraction\ntool, Appendix C for the list of studies included in the\nreview and Appendix D for the characteristics of in-\ncluded studies):\n Bibliographic details\n Evaluation context (details of review datasets tested)\n Evaluation of active learning (if applicable)\n(see below for definition)\n Evaluation of classifier\n Evaluation of feature selection\n Implementation issues\n About the evaluation (the methodology and\nmetrics used)\n Study type descriptors\n Critical appraisal\n Comments and conclusions\nExtraction consisted of two types of data: direct quota-\ntions from the papers, which were gathered through\nline-by-line coding of the papers; and categorical data,\nwhich were gathered by noting the presence or absence\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 6 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5of certain characteristics. These two types of data were\ncollected simultaneously. For example, a tick box was\nchecked if a study reported using a support vector ma-\nchine (SVM) classifier, and line-by-line coding of text\nthat described the SVM was associated with that tick\nbox in the EPPI-Reviewer 4 software [22].\nSynthesis methods\nThe reviewers discussed the key issues that needed to be\ncovered in the review, as well as themes that had\nemerged through extracting data from the studies. On\nthat basis, an outline structure for the synthesis was de-\nveloped. Under the outline subheadings, a narrative was\ndeveloped that drew on both the line-by-line coded text\nand the categorical data. The categorical data allowed\nfor the generation of frequency tables and cross tabula-\ntions that described the state of the evidence base; whilst\nthe coded text allowed for a richer interrogation of the\nemerging themes.\nResults\nThe results are presented in order of the research ques-\ntions posed. Since some issues raised apply beyond the\nsystematic review context, which limited the range of\npapers about text mining that we formally included, we\nhave inserted some commentary (entitled \'further infor-\nmation on this topic\') where information from other do-\nmains may illuminate a specific issue.\nDevelopment of the evidence base\nIn this section, we address research question 1: What is\nthe state of the evidence base related to automating (or\nsemi-automating) the screening stage (based on titles\nand abstracts) of a systematic review?\nChronological developments\nOur 44 included studies fall within the 8 years between\nJanuary 2006 and January 2014—an average of 5.6 evalu-\nations a year. As can be seen in the timeline presented\nin Figure 1, almost every year saw the evaluation of a\nnewly applied type of classifier or some new consider-\nation of the application of text mining to screening.\nIndeed, most papers present a new \'twist\' that distin-\nguishes it from those before, with very few replications\nor comparisons between papers. The developments\nhighlighted in the timeline are those which we had de-\nfined a priori in our data extraction tool and therefore\nalso how the synthesis below is structured; they should\ntherefore be considered to be indicative of interesting\ndevelopments, rather than being a comprehensive list of\nevery innovation (For example, also worthy of note are\nthe decision trees by Frunza and colleagues in 2010 [24];\nand dual supervision and elicited utility by Wallace et al.\n(also in 2010 [25])).This suggests a rapidly evolving evidence base (It also\nhas implications for the later parts of this synthesis, as it\nis difficult to come to any overarching conclusions about\nwhich approach works best.).\nWorkload reduction approaches\nIn this section, we address research question 2: What\nare the stated purposes of (semi-)automating the screen-\ning stage through text mining in terms of workload re-\nduction, and what types of methods have been used to\naddress each purpose?\nIt is evident from the literature that there are several\npossible ways to reduce screening workload. The ap-\nproaches that have received attention in terms of text\nmining are: reducing the number of items that need to\nbe screened manually; reducing the number of people\nneeded to screen the items; increasing the rate (or\nspeed) of screening; and improving workflow. Table 2\nshows the number of studies that implicitly or explicitly\naddressed each of these approaches. Each of these will\nbe discussed in turn.\nReducing the number of items that need to be screened\nIn many reviews, the number of items to be screened is\nvery large. For example, 4 out of the 31 Cochrane Col-\nlaboration systematic reviews published in March 2014\nhad over 10,000 items to screen [26-29]. This can be a\nparticular problem for searches for certain types of study\ndesigns, such as is the case with searches for non-\nrandomised controlled trials, for which database filters\nare not available or consistently used [30]. Large num-\nbers of items to screen is even more evident in non-\nclinical disciplines, in which search strategies tend to be\nbroader in response to broader research questions, less\nprecise or consistent terminology and the lack of con-\ntrolled vocabularies; for example, EPPI-Centre reviews\non topics in public health, education and social care\nregularly exceed 20,000 items to be screened. At its most\nextreme, one review identified upward of 800,000 items\nand another over 1 million items to be screened (see\n[31] for a description of such \'extreme reviewing\'). Given\nthat an experienced reviewer can take between 30 sec-\nonds and several minutes to evaluate a citation [11], the\nwork involved in screening even as \'few\' as several thou-\nsand citations is considerable.\nAn obvious solution to reducing workload is therefore\nto reduce the number of items that need to be screened\nmanually. Historically, the volume of records returned\nfrom a search was determined in part through the search\nstrategy: the number of records identified could be re-\nduced either through searching fewer sources or through\ncarefully constructed database queries. The latter ap-\nproach usually adopted an emphasis on the precision of\nthe search over its recall. However, some method\nFigure 1 Brief timeline of developments in the use of text mining technologies for reducing screening burden in systematic reviews.\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 7 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5guidelines specifically recommend favouring recall over\nprecision in order to avoid missing relevant studies (e.g.,\nthe Campbell Collaboration\'s guide to information re-\ntrieval and the US Institute of Medicine of the National\nAcademies [32,33]).\nTherefore, resource-efficient approaches that maximise\nrecall are needed, and a number of different models have\nbeen identified here. The vast majority of studies in-\ncluded in the review (n = 30) implicitly or explicitly\npropose using text mining for the purpose of reducing\nthe number of studies that need to be screened manu-\nally. Within this set of studies, there are two mainTable 2 The number of studies implicitly or explicitly\naddressing screening workload problems (n = 44)\nWorkload reduction approach Number of studies\nReducing number needed to screen 30\nText mining as a second screener 6\nIncreasing the rate (speed) of screening 7\nImproving workflow through\nscreening prioritisation\n12\nNote. Some studies adopted more than one approach to workload reduction,\nso column total is greater than 44 studies.approaches to excluding items from a review. The first\napproach is to use a classifier that makes explicit in/\nout decisions; 23 studies evaluated this approach\n[11,14,23,25,34-51]. The second approach is to use a\nranking or prioritisation system and then exclude items\nthat fall below some threshold or criterion, or that lie\nwithin a \'negative prediction zone\' [31,52-57]; seven\nstudies used this approach. Whilst many classifiers\nemploying the first approach inherently assign some\nkind of score that indicates confidence in how likely an\nitem is to be an include or exclude (akin to the ranking\nin the second approach), this is usually \'hidden\' from\nthe reviewer such that the decisions are presented as\ncomplete. In contrast, the second approach may re-\nquire a reviewer to continue manual screening until\nthe (reviewer-specified) criterion is met.\nIt is important to note that the final approach, active\nlearning, can fit loosely into both of the abovementioned\ncamps. Active learning (evaluated in nine studies\n[11,23,25,31,40,45,48,49,58]) is an iterative process whereby\nthe accuracy of the predictions made by the machine is im-\nproved through interaction with reviewers. The re-\nviewer—or review team—provides an initial sample of\ninclude/exclude decisions that the machine \'learns\'\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 8 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5from; the machine subsequently generates a ranked list\nand requests the reviewer to provide decisions on items\nhigh in the list that it will learn the most from. The ma-\nchine adapts its decision rule including the information\nfrom the additional items and generates a new list of\nitems for the reviewer to screen. This process continues,\nwith the number of reviewer decisions growing and a\ngreater number of relevant items found than would\notherwise be the case, until a given stopping criterion is\nreached and the process ends. Although the final in-\nclude/exclude decisions for any items not screened\nmanually come from the classifier, the human screener\nstill has some control over the training process and the\npoint at which manual screening ceases.\nIn all cases, authors reported that the systems tested led\nto a reduction in workload; however, given the diversity of\napproaches and the lack of overlap (replication) between\nevaluations, it is impossible to conclude whether one ap-\nproach is better than the other in terms of performance.\nTypical performance reported a reduction in manual\nscreening workload from less than 10% (e.g. [41]) up to\nmore than 90% (e.g. [48]). Where expressed as a work-\nload reduction, studies tended to report reductions of\nbetween approximately 40% and 50% of work saved (e.g.\n[25,40,41,55]). Studies differed from one another in\nterms of the recall that they aimed for. Some expressed\nresults in terms of 95% recall (e.g. [23]), whereas others\nexpressed their results in terms of retrieving all relevant\nstudies (e.g. [48]). Razavi and colleagues took a critical\nperspective with regard to manual decisions too, con-\ncluding that \'Since the machine learning prediction per-\nformance is generally on the same level as the human\nprediction performance, using the described system will\nlead to significant workload reduction for the human\nexperts involved in the systematic review process\' [44].\nText mining as a second screener\nMethods guidance for conducting systematic reviews\noften suggests that more than one person should screen\nall (or some proportion) of the records returned by the\nsearches (e.g., the Institute of Medicine (Washington,\nDC) states in Standard 3.3.3. \'Use two or more members\nof the review team, working independently, to screen\nand select studies\' [33]). The rationale behind this ap-\nproach is that a single screener can inadvertently intro-\nduce bias into the study selection process either because\nof their interpretation of the inclusion criteria or through\ntheir understanding of the content of titles and abstracts.\nMoreover, given the volume of records to be reviewed, it\nis conceivable that some relevant records might \'slip\nthrough the net\'. It is believed that if there is consistency\nin the inclusion decisions amongst two or more independ-\nent screeners, then the screening process is not likely to\nbe biased. This, however, becomes a very labour-intensiveprocess—particularly when the number of records to\nscreen is high. Although some guidance suggests that if\nsufficient inter-reviewer reliability is achieved that it is ac-\nceptable to \'double screen\' only a proportion of the re-\ncords when there is a large number to screen, this still can\nadd a substantial amount of resource to an already time-\nconsuming procedure.\nTo combat this workload issue, six papers have advo-\ncated the use of text mining as a second screener: re-\nplacing or supplementing the additional human reviewer\nthat would be required at this stage [24,30,59-62]. In this\nmodel, one human reviewer screens all of the records\nand the machine acts as the independent check (or pre-\nsents a vastly reduced list of items to be screened to an\nadditional human reviewer). The evaluations of workload\nreduction in this area have all been on a classifier model,\nin which explicit in/out decisions are made by the ma-\nchine. Results from the evaluations are positive—the clas-\nsifiers had good agreement with the human reviewer/s.\nThree of these papers were authored by Bekhuis and col-\nleagues [30,59,60], who report that their approach could\nreduce manual workload by between 88% and 98% [60].\nFrunza and colleagues report two studies in this area\n[24,61] and Garcia one study [62]. Like Bekhuis, they re-\nport positive results from their evaluations, though they\npresent their findings in terms of high recall rather than\nworkload reduction, and so a direct comparison cannot\nbe made.\nIncreasing the rate of screening\nAn alternative approach to those above, which empha-\nsises reducing the number of items that need to be\nscreened manually, is to aid researchers in coming to a\ndecision about each item more quickly; that is, to in-\ncrease the rate of screening. To achieve this, visual data\nmining (VDM) approaches attempt to create a visual\nrepresentation of the connections between documents\n(using term similarity and/or author connections) to as-\nsist the screener in identifying studies easily that are\nmore likely to be similar to each other. Thus, once a\nrelevant document is identified, they can quickly scan\nother documents that appear to be similar to the rele-\nvant document (and similarly, identify documents that\nare likely to be excluded quickly). The approach assumes\nthat humans can make a decision about a study\'s rele-\nvance faster using this additional visual information than\nrelying on the textual information in the titles and ab-\nstracts alone [13].\nFive evaluations of visual data mining were identified\n[13,14,63-65], all in the field of software engineering.\nThe evaluations of visual data mining differ from evalua-\ntions of other text mining approaches in that they em-\nploy a controlled trial evaluation design to compare the\nspeed and accuracy with which a human can screen\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 9 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5items using VDM or without using VDM. The results sug-\ngest that humans can screen faster with VDM aids than\nwithout, although the accuracy of the human screeners\ndoes not appear to change substantially [13,14,63-65].\nA second approach to speeding up the rate of screen-\ning that is embedded within approaches to reducing the\nnumber needed to screen is through efficient citation as-\nsignment. The only example that was identified of this\ntype was by Wallace and colleagues [49]. In that paper,\nthe authors emphasise that most review teams have a\ncombination of expert and novice screeners. Within the\ncontext of an active learning approach, they developed an\nalgorithm that incorporates both information about the\nrelevance of each item and the expected time that it will\ntake to annotate that item; on that basis, the algorithm se-\nlects citations specifically for expert and novice reviewers\nto label. The authors reported that this approach enabled\nmore items to be screened in the same amount of time\ncompared with typical active learning approaches.\nImproving workflow efficiency through screening\nprioritisation\nScreening prioritisation is ultimately a form of efficient cit-\nation assignment, in that it aims to present reviewers with\nan ordered list of the items, with the items that are most\nlikely to be relevant to their review at the top of the list.\nHowever, it differs from the model described by Wallace\net al. [49] in that it is not necessarily embedded within an\napproach that is attempting to reduce the number needed\nto screen and it does not differentially assign items to dif-\nferent types of reviewers (i.e., experts versus novices).\nThere are various proposed benefits of this approach\nto workflow efficiency. One is that reviewers gain a bet-\nter understanding of the inclusion criteria earlier in the\nprocess, as they encounter more examples of relevant\nstudies sooner than would otherwise be the case. It also\nenables the retrieval of the full text of documents to\nstart sooner than can occur when citations are screened\nessentially at random. This can be important, as obtain-\ning the full-text reports brings forward their full-text\nscreening, the checking of their bibliographies and, crit-\nically, enables contact to be made with study authors\nmuch earlier in the review. It is also possible that this\nwill make the screening process faster, once the vast ma-\njority of relevant studies are identified, as the screeners\nbecome more confident that items later in the list are\nless likely to be relevant. This could also help with the\nproblem of over-inclusiveness that is often experienced\nin reviews, in which reviewers tend to be cautious and\ninclude many more items at this early stage than ultim-\nately make it into the review.\nCohen highlighted another potential benefit: \'In reviews\nwith searches that result in a large number of citations to\nbe screened for retrieval, reviewing the documents inorder of their likely importance would be particularly use-\nful. The remainder of the citations could be screened over\nthe following months, perhaps by the members of the\nteam with less experience, whilst the work of reviewing\nthe includable studies is ongoing\' ([66] p. 692) (An on-\ngoing project at the EPPI-Centre, which had a large vol-\nume of items to be screened (>38,000) but with a very\ntight timeframe, has taken advantage of this benefit [67].).\nThere are also potential benefits for review updates.\nCohen stated that \'by reviewing the most likely import-\nant documents before other documents, the human re-\nviewers or curators are more likely to be able to "get up\nto speed" on the current developments within a domain\nmore quickly\' ([68] p. 121). In quite a different applica-\ntion of text mining to the screening process, Cohen later\nexplored the use of prioritisation for identifying when a\nreview update was required, which would involve send-\ning alerts to the review team when likely relevant new\nstudies are published [69].\nIn other words, this approach emphasises improving\nworkflow in a review and has proposed benefits for effi-\nciency beyond reducing workload in the title and abstract\nscreening phase. Four studies adopted a prioritisation ap-\nproach to improve workflow [58,66,68,69]. All four evalua-\ntions reported benefits of this approach.\nNote that screening prioritisation can also be used to\nreduce the number of items needed to be screened if a\nscreening cut-off criterion is established (see section on\nthis workload reduction approach, above). Seven studies\nthat have used screening prioritisation did so to reduce\nthe number needed to screen and reported benefits in\nterms of the amount of work saved [31,52-57]. (Again,\nthe metrics and processes varied, so it is not possible to\nestimate overall or mean statistics across these studies).\nSpecific issues relating to the use of text mining in\nsystematic reviews\nIn this section, we address research question 3: How\nhave key contextual problems of applying text mining to\nsystematic review screening been addressed? These reflect\nthe challenges that need to be addressed when applying\nmethods developed for other applications to the case of\nsystematic review screening.\nThe importance of high recall for systematic reviews\nAs mentioned in the \'Background\' section, recall is often\nprioritised over precision in systematic reviews. This is\nbecause it is generally considered to be critical to re-\ntrieve all relevant items to avoid biasing the review find-\nings. The importance of high recall of relevant studies is\nlikely to be critical in the acceptability and uptake of text\nmining techniques by the systematic review community.\nIndeed, the authors of one paper reflected that \'If those\nwho rely on systematic review to develop guidelines and\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 10 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5policy demand 100% recall and informatics approaches\nsuch as ours are not able to guarantee 100% recall, the\napproaches may be doomed\' ([23] p. 15).\nMany of the studies in this review explicitly refer to\nthe importance of high recall and the implications it\nmight have for text mining applications in this area\n(studies which discuss the importance of high recall in-\nclude [11,23,24,30,38,40,41,44,48,49,53,54,58,60,61,70]).\nHowever, few of the studies directly built into the technol-\nogy an approach to maximising recall. Those that did dir-\nectly attempt to maximise recall are discussed below.Voting or committee approaches for ensuring high recall\nOne approach to ensuring that studies are not missed is\nto use a voting or committee approach. Essentially, mul-\ntiple classifiers are run simultaneously, and then a \'vote\'\nis taken on each item to determine whether it is likely to\nbe relevant or not. A conservative approach would be to\nput forward for human screening any item that receives at\nleast one \'include vote\' (e.g., Wallace et al. [11]); an ap-\nproach that places additional emphasis on precision might\nset a minimum number of agreeing votes (e.g., >50% of\nthe classifiers must agree that an item is an include [44]).\nThe appeal of such approaches is that the classification\ndecision is less susceptible to missing studies that do not\nresemble the training set of includes, because each clas-\nsifier can start with a different training set. Several stud-\nies have used this approach, with different numbers of\nclassifiers used in the committee. Razavi used a commit-\ntee of five classifiers [44]; Wallace and Frunza used (up\nto) eleven classifiers [11,24,61]; Ma used two classifiers\n[40]. Only Frunza has considered whether the number\nof votes makes a difference, as discussed below [24,61].\nIn Frunza (2010), if at least one decision for an ab-\nstract was to include it in the systematic review, then\nthe final label was \'Included\' [24]. They then tested\nwhether the number of votes (i.e., number of classifiers)\nmade a difference to recall and precision. They con-\ncluded that the 2-vote technique is superior to the other\nvoting techniques (1-vote, 3-vote, 4-vote) in terms of the\nF measure and work saved over sampling (WSS). The\nhighest level of recall was achieved through the 4-vote\ntechnique. The success of combined human-machine\nscreening was similar in their later study [61], with the\nconclusion that the 2-vote technique was the best per-\nformer. Importantly, Frunza noted that precision de-\ncreased slightly when the human decisions were added\nto the machine decisions (i.e., the human incorrectly in-\ncluded some items). This might be relevant to the obser-\nvation that human screeners tend to be over-inclusive\n(discussed in a later section).\n(We will return to the issue of \'voting\' approaches\nbelow, in the section on \'Hasty generalisation\').Specialist algorithms\nAt least three types of classifiers have been modified to in-\nclude a specialist algorithm that adjusts the learning rate\nof the classifier to penalise false negatives. Cohen et al. ap-\nplied a \'false negative learning rate\' to their voting percep-\ntron classifier expressing this as a \'cost-proportionate\nrejection sampling\' strategy [36]. Matwin et al. added a\nheuristic weight factorization technique to their comple-\nment naïve Bayes (CNB) algorithm to maximise recall\nwhen their original algorithm had unacceptably low recall\n(<95%) [41]. Bekhuis also modified a complement naïve\nBayes classifier by optimising the decision parameters\nusing F3: a summary measure of performance that over-\nweights recall relative to precision [60]. Wallace and col-\nleagues modified their support vector machine approach\nto penalise more severely for false negatives compared\nwith false positives [48].\nAll of these studies were retrospective evaluations in\nwhich the performance of a classifier was compared\nagainst completed include decisions and all reported\ngood results in terms of recall and workload reduction.\nFuture evaluations of this approach should consider\nwhether the amount and/or quality of the training data\nmake a difference to the ability of these modifications to\nadequately penalise false negatives. The reason for this is\nthat, if used in a \'live\' review, there might be only a small\nnumber of human-labelled items in the training set to\nbe able to determine whether the classifier has incor-\nrectly rejected a relevant study. If there are only a small\nnumber of includable studies in the entire dataset, then\nsuch penalties might not be implementable.\nHuman input\nMa proposed using active learning as a method for as-\nsuring high recall [40]. The logic behind this is that the\nalgorithm continues to \'learn\' as more items are manu-\nally screened and so the decision rule is adaptable and\nless reliant on the initial training set. However, Ma\'s [40]\nresults suggest that recall actually declined when active\nlearning was added to a support vector machine or deci-\nsion tree classifier and made no difference to the recall\nof a naïve Bayes classifier. Further research on this is\nneeded to determine why this might be the case.\nHasty generalisation\nThe term \'hasty generalisation\' refers to a bias which can\noccur because the features in the training set are not\nrepresentative of the population; as opposed to other\nforms of \'biased training sets\' (e.g. where bias occurs\nfrom non-randomised sampling). If the initial training\nset of documents in a systematic review is not fully rep-\nresentative of the range of documents which are of inter-\nest, it is possible that these documents will be missing\nfrom the set of studies identified as relevant through\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 11 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5automation (see [25]). To exclude relevant studies due\nto their use of different terminology from those that are\nincluded would be to inject a systematic bias which\nwould be unacceptable in the vast majority of reviews.\nSeveral methods for dealing with this have been evalu-\nated or discussed: drawing on reviewer domain know-\nledge, using patient active learning methods and\nemploying an ensemble of classifiers that vote on\nwhether an item should be included or not. These are\nelaborated on in the following sections.\nReviewer domain knowledge\nSome studies evaluated or discussed drawing on the\nknowledge of the human reviewers to play a part in the\ntext mining process. This is particularly suited to active\nlearning approaches. Jonnalagadda and colleagues sug-\ngested that, in active learning, \'the dynamically changing\nquery set, which decides which document will be pre-\nsented next, could be easily modified at any stage by re-\nmoving or adding terms to the query set. In this way,\nthe possibility of not finding documents that use differ-\nent words could be further minimised by allowing active\nparticipation of the users in defining the terms in the\nquery set\' ([23] p. 15). They did not, however, test this\napproach empirically.\nIn addition to other text mining methods, Shemilt\net al. employed an approach that used \'reviewer terms\'\n(terms specified by the review team as being indicative\nof an includable or excludable study) [31]. The text con-\ntained in each title-abstract record that was yet to be\nscreened was analysed and the number of relevant and\nirrelevant terms they contained was calculated. A simple\nratio of these values was then generated, and items were\nranked according to this ratio. The authors argue that\n\'The purpose of this method is to act as a counterpoint\nto the automated technologies; whereas in ATR [auto-\nmatic term recognition] and AC [automatic classifica-\ntion], the results are heavily determined by those studies\nalready identified as being relevant; RT [reviewer terms]\noffers another perspective on potential relevance, offer-\ning some protection against the problem of hasty\ngeneralization\' ([31] p. 45). This might offer reassurance\nto review teams that no relevant items are being errone-\nously discarded and is an easy approach to implement if\nthe reviewers are familiar with the key terminology.\nA more holistic approach was evaluated by Wallace\net al. [25]. As in Shemilt et al. (above), reviewers pro-\nvided terms that were indicative of includes and excludes\n(although the terms were ranked in order of \'indicative-\nness\' in the Wallace paper).
