Wallace et al. suggested that\ncombining prior reviewer knowledge with the machine\nmodel could be more effective at avoiding hasty general-\nisation and tested a variety of combinations in terms of\nthe timing at which the reviewer knowledge rankingswere emphasised relative to the machine labelling. They\nconcluded that beginning with a bias towards the reviewer\nrankings and subsequently decreasing its importance as la-\nbelling proceeds would be the most effective way of com-\nbining reviewer domain knowledge in the process; however,\nthey also noted \'How this should be done precisely remains\na problem for future work\' ([25] p. 8).\nIn addition, in a study which came to light after our\nformal searches were complete, Small et al. utilised re-\nviewer \'labelled features\' within what they called a \'con-\nstrained weight space SVM\' [71]. They found that, by\nallowing reviewers to influence the decisions made by\nthe classifier, it is possible to obtain better results with\nsmaller samples of training records.\nPatient active learning\n\'Patient active learning\' was first proposed by Wallace\net al. as a means of overcoming hasty generalisation using\nan active learning approach [11]. The distinguishing fea-\nture of \'patient\' active learning is that training is based on\ndifferent \'views\' of the records (e.g. classifiers based on ti-\ntles or abstract or MeSH terms) which are selected at ran-\ndom at each iteration of the active learning process. The\nadditional variability that this approach injects into the\nprocess above the use of a single \'view\' aims to ensure that\nthe system as a whole is exposed to as wide a variety of\nrelevant studies as possible and thus does not overly nar-\nrow the range of items it considers to be relevant.\nWallace and colleagues evaluated four different active\nlearning strategies and found that patient active learning\noutperformed the others [11]. In a study which repli-\ncated some of Wallace\'s work on the same data, Miwa\nand colleagues evaluated a range of active learning en-\nhancements and found that patient active learning is cer-\ntainly better than some strategies, though not as good as\nothers [45].\nVoting or committee approaches for dealing with hasty\ngeneralisation\nThe concept of a committee of classifiers was earlier in-\ntroduced for helping to ensure high recall. Given that\nhasty generalisation would logically lead to lower recall,\nit is unsurprising that this approach has also been sug-\ngested as a solution to hasty generalisation.\nTwo studies explicitly refer to this approach. Miwa\net al. reported that voting showed some improvement\nover non-voting approaches, especially for one particu-\nlarly \'messy\' dataset with respect to the terminology used\nin that review topic [45]. Shemilt et al. did not compare\nvoting with non-voting approaches but ran the classifier\nmultiple times and then manually screened only those\nitems that were consistently classified as being relevant\n[31]. This approach seems likely to have increased preci-\nsion at the expense of sensitivity.\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 12 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5Dealing with imbalanced datasets\nAt the title and abstract screening stage of a typical sys-\ntematic review, the dataset is imbalanced in that there are\nusually far more excluded studies than included studies.\nOne paper reported a median search precision (number of\nincluded studies divided by total number of items located\nthrough searching) of 2.9% across 94 health-related sys-\ntematic reviews [72]. This translates to an imbalance in\nwhich there are approximately 33.5 times as many ex-\ncludes as includes. Search precision can be much less than\nthis, resulting in even greater imbalances.\nIn text mining evaluations, this is referred to as the\n\'class imbalance\' problem (where \'class\' refers to the des-\nignation as an include or an exclude). It is a problem for\ntext mining as there are far fewer relevant items com-\npared to non-relevant items on which to train the classi-\nfier or text mining technology. Also, Wallace et al. state\nthat \'class imbalance presents a problem for classifica-\ntion algorithms, because they have typically been opti-\nmised for accuracy, rather than the recall of a particular\nclass\' ([11] p. 5). Since it is possible to have high accur-\nacy even if a system produces many false negatives [73],\nthis could be a problem for systematic reviews where\nmissing relevant studies is highly undesirable.\nTo counter the class imbalance, various methods have\nbeen proposed. They generally rely on up-weighting the\nnumber of includes or down-weighting the number of\nexcludes; or undersampling the number of excludes used\nin the training set. The various approaches are described\nin the following sections.Weighting\nWeighting approaches assign greater weights to positive\ninstances (includes) than to negative instances (ex-\ncludes). Generally, the weight is set to the ratio of the\nnumber of positive instances to the number of negative\ninstances.\nCompared to an un-weighted method or an aggressive\nundersampling method (described below), Miwa et al.\nreported better performance of active learning models\non a variety of imbalanced datasets [45]. This was par-\nticularly the case when weighting was used in conjunc-\ntion with a \'certainty\' approach, in which the next items\nto be annotated in the active learning process were se-\nlected because they had the highest probability of being\nrelevant to the review, based on the output of classifiers\ntrained on previously annotated items.\nCohen et al. also reported good results for a weighted\nmodel, in which they modified their voting perceptron\nclassifier to incorporate a false negative learning rate\n(FNLR) [36]. Across 15 reviews, they found that the FNLR\nshould be proportional to the ratio of negative to positive\nsamples in the dataset in order to maximise performance.Undersampling\nUndersampling involves using fewer non-relevant stud-\nies in the training set than might be expected given their\nprevalence in the entire dataset. Two different types of\nundersampling have been tested in this context: random\nand aggressive.\nRandom undersampling involves randomly selecting a\ntraining set with the same number of relevant and non-\nrelevant studies. This approach was adopted in four stud-\nies that did not compare random undersampling to other\nmethods for dealing with class imbalance [11,31,39,48].\nMa compared five undersampling methods with their ac-\ntive learning naïve Bayes classifier—one of which was ran-\ndom undersampling [40]. Method 1 involved selecting the\nnegative examples whose average distances (a measure of\nsimilarity/dissimilarity) to the three farthest positive exam-\nples are the smallest; Method 2 involved selecting the\nnegative examples whose average distances to the three\nclosest positive examples are the smallest; Method 3 in-\nvolved selecting the negative examples whose average dis-\ntances to the three closest positive examples are the\nlargest; Method 4 involved removing those examples that\nparticipated in Tomek links (see [74] for a definition);\nMethod 5 involved selecting negative examples randomly.\nMa concluded that random undersampling did not per-\nform the best. \'In general, the first and third undersampling\nmethods work well with all feature selection methods. We\nhave a very high recall after performing undersampling\ntechniques. However, we have a big trade-off in precision\'\n([40] p. 75).\nAggressive undersampling as defined by Wallace (in\nthe context of active learning) involves discarding the\nmajority examples (i.e., excludes) nearest the current\nseparating hyperplane [11]. The separating hyperplane\nrepresents the border between the two classes: includes\nand excludes. Therefore, by throwing away those nearest\nto the hyperplane, we are discarding those that are the\nmost ambiguous as to whether they should be in the in-\nclude or exclude class. As such, the items that are more\nlikely to be excludes are sent to the human reviewer for\nmanual screening, which are then used to retrain the clas-\nsifier. The logic behind this approach is to \'explicitly push\nthe decision boundary away from the minority class [in-\ncludes], as it has been observed that when there is class\nimbalance, SVMs are prone to discovering hyperplanes\nthat are closer to the minority class than the ideal separat-\ning boundary, resulting in false negatives\' ([11] p. 5).\nWallace (2010a) [11] compared naive random sam-\npling and aggressive undersampling in their evaluation\nof active learning with an SVM classifier. They con-\ncluded that aggressive undersampling performed better\n[11]. Miwa et al. compared aggressive undersampling\nwith a range of other options and found that whilst it\noutperformed the other strategies at the beginning of\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 13 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5the active learning sequence, other methods overtook it\nas screening progressed [45].\nIt is difficult to draw conclusions across the papers, as\nthe two that conducted a comparison differed in many\nother dimensions (classifier, reviews tested, etc.). This re-\nquires further exploration.\nCohen and colleagues observed that any kind of sam-\npling strategy can result in the exclusion of a large propor-\ntion of the possible sample available from which the\nclassifier can \'learn\' [66]. \'To address this, we sample the\nnontopic data, creating several different priming SVM\nmodels, and extract the support vectors from each of these\nmodels to use as priming vectors. The nontopic data are\nrejection sampled, that is, sampled without replacement.\nThe probabilities of inclusion for each sample within a\ngiven nontopic are adjusted so that approximately the\nsame number of samples from each nontopic is included.\'\nIn their experiments they used 20 resamples.\nOther methods for dealing with class imbalance\nSome authors claimed that certain classifiers are particu-\nlarly well suited to imbalanced datasets. Bekhuis Frunza,\nKouznetsov and Matwin claimed that complement naïve\nBayes (CNB) is suitable for imbalanced data, particularly\nwhen implemented in Weka [24,30,41,54,60,61]. Frunza\nand colleagues compared CNB with other classifiers (de-\ncision trees, support vector machine, instance-based\nlearning and boosting) but concluded that CNB always\nperformed better; it is not clear, however, whether this is\nbecause of the class imbalance problem or other differ-\nences between the approaches [24,61].\nSome authors have suggested that the selection of fea-\ntures for text mining might be important in addressing\nclass imbalances. Although they did not test it in their\npaper, Bekhuis et al. suggested that selecting features\nwithin the positive (include) and negative (exclude) classes\nbefore grid optimization, rather than across all items,\nwould be appropriate for dealing with class imbalance [30].\nFrunza explicitly compared classifiers that had been\n\'boosted\' in terms of having more representative features\nfor the included class (a balanced dataset) with typical fea-\nture selection technique (imbalanced dataset) but found no\nsignificant difference between these two approaches [24].\nUpdates versus \'new\' reviews\nOut of the 44 studies, the context of 36 was a new re-\nview, eight a review update, and for two studies the re-\nview context was not the primary area of investigation\n(the issue was the performance of classifiers). The con-\ntext of new reviews is challenging, because there is so lit-\ntle training material available at the start of screening on\nwhich to conduct any machine learning. Whilst the con-\ncept of obtaining an unbiased set of training material\nusing a random sample is widely employed, Wallace andcolleagues have outlined an explicit iterative method to\ndetermine whether the variation in likely \'includes\' has\nbeen explored adequately enough for active learning to\nbegin [11]. They do this drawing on the work of Brinker\nwho has developed methods for incorporating diversity\nin active learning by evaluating the stability of a measure\nof similarity between \'included\' citations between itera-\ntions [75]. Once the measure of similarity ceases to\nchange between iterations, the sample can be considered\nready to perform active learning.\nIn contrast, whilst the review update might appear to\nbe the more straightforward situation, since there are\npreexisting citation decisions on which to \'learn\', some\nof the earliest work included in our review—by Cohen—\nshows that review updates face many challenges of their\nown [35,66,68,69]. In particular, the issue of \'concept\ndrift\' looms large over the review update. As Bekhuis\npoints out, there are many changing variables in a re-\nview update—the team, the searches and even aspects of\nthe question may all change—and the data from the ori-\nginal review may cease to be a reliable indicator of what\nshould be included in the new one [60]. Dalal and col-\nleagues attempted to mitigate the effects of concept drift\nbut were not entirely successful [70].\nAdditional information on this topic\nOnline learning methods which treat datasets as a\nstream, updating their model for each instance and dis-\ncarding it after updates, can be used for new reviews.\nSome online learning algorithms adapt their models\nquickly to new coming data and can be adapted to deal\nwith slight concept drift [76]. Domain adaptation, multi-\ntask learning and transfer learning can improve models\nfor a specific review by using related information from\nother reviews and problems. Such learning methods sup-\nport the learning of multiple, related review targets [77].\nHow has the workload reduction issue been evaluated?\nThe following section addresses research question 4: How\nhas the workload reduction issue been evaluated? There are\nthree aspects that we explore: what has been compared and\nthrough what research design; and what metrics were used\nto evaluate the performance of the technologies?\nWhat has been compared, using what research design?\nThe vast majority of evaluations used a retrospective de-\nsign; that is, they assessed performance against the \'gold\nstandard\' judgements made in a completed systematic re-\nview [11,25,30,34,36-45,47,48,51,52,55,56,59-62,66,68,70]\n(n = 27). In contrast, prospective designs are those in\nwhich the technology was assessed in a \'live\' context; that\nis, as the review was being conducted. Seventeen studies\nemployed a prospective design, of which five were self-\ndescribed as \'case studies\' [31,46,50,57,63], four were\ncontrolled trials [13,14,64,65], and eight were other pro-\nspective designs [23,24,35,49,53,54,58,69].\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 14 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5The type of design is important, as prospective designs\nhave the potential to tell us more about how the text\nmining technologies might work when implemented in\n\'real life\'. Whilst retrospective simulations are essential in\ndetermining the relative performance of different classi-\nfiers or establishing the optimal parameters of a classifier,\nsome of the difficulties of implementing such technologies\nin a live review cannot be taken into account adequately\n(e.g., reviewer over-inclusiveness at different stages of the\nprocess, which might \'mislead\' the classifier about what an\ninclude \'looks like\'). Moreover, many of the evaluations\nare of relatively \'neat\' datasets, in that they have a suffi-\ncient number of includes on which to train (even if they\nare the minority class). How does text mining cope when\nthere is a tiny number of includes, or in a so-called \'empty\'\nreview, in which there are no included studies?b\nRelated to the issue of how the technologies were eval-\nuated is the question of what was evaluated. Most of the\nevaluations conducted to date (n = 29) make some form of\ncomparison between different algorithms or methods\nfor text mining [11,23-25,30,34,36,37,39-43,45,49,51-55,58,\n60-62,66,68-70]. The main issues evaluated are: the rela-\ntive effectiveness of different methods for classifying stud-\nies (i.e. \'classifiers\' and different options for using them\n(\'kernels\')); how different approaches to \'feature selection\'\n(the way that aspects of studies—e.g. their titles, abstracts\nand MeSH headings are encoded for machine learning)\nimpact on performance; how effective different ap-\nproaches to separating different pieces of \'intelligence\'\nabout the study are (e.g. separating titles from ab-\nstracts); and whether performance differs depending on\nhow many studies are used for the initial training. The\nremaining 16 evaluations do not compare aspects of the\nmethodology; rather, they report on the effectiveness of\none chosen method for implementing text mining\n[13,14,31,35,38,44,46-48,50,56,57,63-65].\nUnsurprisingly, study design is associated with certain\ntypes of comparisons (see Table 3). The four controlled\ntrials all compared human performance with machine\nperformance but did not compare different aspects of\ntext mining technologies. None of the five case studies\ncompared text mining features either, with an emphasis\ninstead on how workload could be reduced in an ongoing\nreview. The retrospective simulation studies tended to\ncompare more features of text mining than other pro-\nspective studies, perhaps because of the comparative ease\nwith which adaptations to the text mining approach can\nbe made in a retrospective evaluation.\nMetrics for assessing classifier performance\nIn this section, we address research question 3: What\nmetrics are available for evaluating the performance of the\napproaches, in terms of both effectiveness and efficiency?\nThe metrics are presented in order from the most popularto the least in Table 1. Most studies reported more than\none performance metric and generally considered the\nimportance of both identifying relevant studies and re-\nducing workload for the reviewers. The metrics are de-\nfined in Table 1.\nThere are various arguments used throughout the litera-\nture as to which metric is the most appropriate. It should\nbe noted that not all metrics are suitable for all evaluation\ndesigns or text mining technology types. For instance,\ncoverage is only suitable for active learning approaches,\nwhilst Cohen noted that \'If the task is not to separate doc-\numents into positive and negative groups, but instead to\nprioritise which documents should be reviewed first and\nwhich later, then precision, recall and F measure do not\nprovide sufficient information\' (p. 121) [68].\nMeasures that allow the trade-off between recall and\nprecision to be taken into account on a review-by-\nreview basis seem particularly useful, as they allow re-\nviewers to change the relative importance of these two\nmetrics depending on priorities in a given review. These\nmetrics include notably the F measure, work saved over\nsampling and utility, which are summarised below.\nF measure is a weighted harmonic mean of precision\nand recall. The weighting can be determined on a review-\nby-review basis, allowing reviewers to assess the relative\nimportance of recall and precision in their context.\nWork saved over sampling (WSS) indicates how much\nwork (in terms of number of items needed to screen) is\nsaved over and above the work saved by simple sampling\nfor a given level of recall. It is typical to use a recall level\nof 0.95. See Cohen et al. [36].\nUtility is relevant for active learning approaches and is\ncalculated based on yield and burden. Yield represents the\nfraction of includes in the data pool that are identified by\na given method, and burden represents the fraction of in-\ncludes in the data pool that have to be annotated/reviewed\nby reviewers. The formula to calculate utility includes a\nweighting factor so that the reviews can specify the relative\nimportance of yield and burden. This weighting factor has\nbeen established for some contexts but might need to be\nre-established for application in other settings [25].\nIt is clear from the three metrics above that there is a\nsubjective element to the performance metrics, as it is\nup to the evaluators to determine thresholds and weight-\ning values. Whilst this has the advantage of making the\nmetrics tailored to the review and evaluation context, it\n(a) makes it difficult to compare across studies that use\ndifferent thresholds/weights in their calculations, and\n(b) it is not always transparent or justified as to how the\nthresholds/weights were selected.\nEvaluation metrics that emphasise high recall\nAs mentioned above, many studies discussed the import-\nance of high recall without necessarily making explicit\nTable 3 Cross tabulation showing the number of studies employing certain research designs by the aspects of text\nmining that were compared (n = 44)\nWhat aspect of text mining\nwas compared\nRetrospective\nsimulation\nProspective—\ncase study\nProspective—\ncontrolled trial\nProspective—other Total—what\nwas compared\nClassifiers/ algorithms 13 0 0 3 16\nNumber of features 2 0 0 0 2\nFeature extraction/sets (e.g., BoW) 8 0 0 2 10\nViews (e.g., T&A, MeSH) 5 0 0 1 6\nTraining set size 2 0 0 0 2\nKernels 2 0 0 0 2\nTopic specific versus\ngeneral training data\n3 0 0 1 4\nOther optimisations 9 0 0 4 13\nNo comparison 5 5 4 1\nTotal—study design\n(duplicates removed)\n(27) (5) (4) (8)\nNote. Many studies compared more than one aspect of text mining, therefore column total for \'Total—what was compared\' sums to greater than 44. The row for\n\'Total—study design (duplicates removed)\' shows the number of studies of each design type rather than the column totals, as the column totals would include\nduplications of the same studies that compared multiple aspects of text mining technologies.\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 15 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5adaptations to their text mining approach. They do,\nhowever, consider the importance of high recall in their\nchoice of metric when evaluating the performance of the\ntext mining technology. Examples included:\n Bekhuis (2012) used F3—a summary measure that\noverweights recall relative to precision—because\nthey felt this was more in keeping with reviewer\nbehaviour (than a metric which weights them\nequally) [59]\n Kouznetsov (2010) used false negatives (relevant\narticles mistakenly ranked at the bottom of a ranked\nlist) as their primary performance measure [54]\n Wallace (2011) [58] used U19—a weighted metric in\nwhich recall is 19 times as important as cost. The\nvalue of 19 was determined through an expert\nconsultation process [25] (see Wallace [11])\n Dalal (2013) evaluated performance using a range of\nprobability thresholds to better consider the impact\non observed performance of using different recall\nand precision trade-offs: one metric was based on\n\'sensitivity-maximising thresholds\' whilst another\n\'preserved good sensitivity whilst substantially\nreducing the error rate [false positives]\' (p. 348) [70]\nIn contrast to most of the studies in this review, Dalal\n(2013) argued that \'neither error minimization nor sensi-\ntivity maximisation are absolute goals\' (p. 348) [70]. In\nfact, Fiszman and colleagues (2008, 2010) used the F0.5\nmeasure, which weights precision more highly than re-\ncall [38,53]. They argue that clinical practice guideline\ndevelopers value precision more than recall and there-\nfore performance should be evaluated on this basis. Thissuggests that the relative importance of recall and preci-\nsion might vary from context-to-context, and a high re-\ncall should not be assumed to be more important than\nhigh precision (though in most systematic review guid-\nance—and practice—maximising recall is prioritised).\nEvaluation metrics that account for class imbalance\nAs with the issue of the importance of high recall in sys-\ntematic reviews, some authors have reflected the class\nimbalance problem in their choice of evaluation meas-\nure. Cohen (2010) argued that the AUC is independent\nof class prevalence [24,35], whilst Frunza [24] reported\nthe F measure for the same reason. The choice of evalu-\nation metric should consider whether class imbalance is\nlikely to bias the results.\nFurther information on this topic\nWe should note that other evaluation metrics can also\naccount for class imbalance. For example, if you care\nabout both the TPs and the TNs, you\'d use ROC-AUC,\nbut if you only care about the TPs, you might prefer\nPR_AUC [78]. See also [79].\nImplementation challenges\nThe following section attempts to answer research ques-\ntion 5: What challenges to implementation emerge from\nreviewing the evidence base? Whilst almost all of the pa-\npers concluded that text mining was a \'promising\' ap-\nproach to reduce workload in the screening stage of a\nsystematic review, it was not always clear how these\ntechnologies would be rolled out for use in \'live\' reviews.\nA few issues became clear that need to be considered for\nthe knowledge gained in these studies to have practical\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 16 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5application (all of which apply to other uses of automa-\ntion and semi-automation in systematic reviews [80]).\nDeployed systems\nOnly six different systems (reported in 12 papers) are\ncurrently \'deployed\'—that is, are in a packaged system\nthat a reviewer could use without having to do any com-\nputer programming. Some are bespoke systematic review\nsystems, whereas others are more generic software for\npredictive analytics which can be used in a systematic\nreview. The bespoke systems for systematic reviews\nwhich were used in evaluations in this review are:\nAbstrackr [49,50], EPPI-Reviewer [31,57], GAPScreener\n[51] and Revis [64]. Many generic software applications\nsupport the kinds of machine learning evaluated in this re-\nview; the two that were used in our included papers were\nPimiento [62] and RapidMiner [59,60]. However, even\nthough no programming may be required to use these\ntools, reviewers using the systems are likely to require\nsome training to be able to use them. Given concerns\nabout the need for high recall, imbalanced datasets, etc.,\nthese are not packages that can be used without under-\nstanding some of the behind-the-scenes decisions that are\nmade with respect to handling the data.\nReplication of evaluations\nOnly one study in the evidence base represents a true\nreplication of another study (Felizardo [65]). There are\nsome partial replications that used the same dataset; not-\nably, Cohen and colleagues and Matwin and colleagues\nhad an ongoing correspondence in the Journal of the\nAmerican Medical Informatics Association in which they\npresented results across the same review datasets using\ndifferent classifiers and parameters. Most studies differ\nin many ways: datasets used, classifiers tested, feature se-\nlection processes applied, citation portions viewed, com-\nparisons made, study designs employed, metrics used for\nevaluation, etc. This makes it impossible to compare re-\nsults across studies directly. It also makes it difficult to\nconclude whether any particular aspect of the above-\nmentioned differences is particularly important to adopt\nor fruitful to explore in future research.\nIt is hoped that future evaluations will attempt more\nreplications of the same methodological applications but\non different datasets, to determine whether findings hold\nwhen applied to new topic areas. For instance, Miwa\n[45] reported that a particular approach did not perform\nas well on \'messy\' social science datasets as it did for\n\'cleaner\' clinical datasets that had been used elsewhere\n(though other enhancements can make up for some of\nthis deficit)—these sorts of partial replications of the\nmethod are helpful in understanding the cross-review\nand cross-disciplinary applicability of the evaluation\nfindings [45].Scalability\nA further concern is whether some of the approaches\nwill work on very large datasets—that is, can they be\n\'scaled up\' from the small datasets used in the evalua-\ntions to the larger datasets that are often encountered in\nsystematic reviews. The largest evaluation was on a data-\nset of more than 1 million citations [31], although that\nwas a case study (and an extreme one at that!); the sec-\nond largest evaluation was on a dataset of 47,274 [24].\nHowever, the vast majority were conducted on review\ndatasets that were well below 5,000 items, with the smal-\nlest datasets being only 57 items (20 in the training set,\n37 in the test set; [64,65]).\nGiven that the purpose of using such technologies in\nsystematic reviews is to reduce screening workload, then it\nseems appropriate to test them on datasets for which the\nworkload is large or even unmanageable. Although we can\nextrapolate from the smaller datasets to larger reviews,\nthere is a limit to how much we can assume that the tech-\nnologies will be able to detect true positives in such large\n(and thereby presumably more diverse) datasets.\nThe issue of scalability is particularly relevant to the vis-\nual text mining approaches, as discussed earlier in the\npaper. Consideration will need to be paid to how to repre-\nsent connections between papers visually when many\nitems are in the dataset; the visual image could be too\noverwhelming to be of any use in aiding human informa-\ntion processing. Either adaptations to such tools will need\nto be made for scaling up, or an upper threshold of num-\nber of items in the dataset might need to be established.\nFurther information on this topic\nMethods such as stream-based active learning are promis-\ning in handling large-scale data instances [81]. Stream ac-\ntive learning is closely related to online learning [3.3.4],\nbut as it does not need to store all the instances in active\nlearning, it can handle large-scale data instances.\nSuitability. Appropriateness of TM for a given review\nThis systematic review has aimed to identify all the rele-\nvant studies concerning the use of text mining for\nscreening, finding that it is a relatively new field with\nmany gaps in the evidence base. One significant gap is\nthe limited range of topics and types of study within the\nreviews which have been used to evaluate the text min-\ning methods. On the whole, they are concerned with\nidentifying RCTs in clinical areas and there are almost\nno examples outside the health and biomedical sector\napart from a discrete set in the area of software engin-\neering. This is not surprising, since these are the areas that\ntext mining for other purposes is most common, but it is\nan important area for future research, because general lit-\nerature is more challenging to text mine because of the\nvariability of concepts, text categorisation, etc.\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 17 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5Bekhuis and Demner-Fushman tested this explicitly in\ntheir study of 2010, looking for non-randomised, as well\nas randomised, controlled trials (though still in the\nmedical domain) [59]. Their findings are promising,\nthough they are concerned about the possibility of\n\'over-fitting\' and the danger of building a classifier that\ndoes not recognise the true scope of relevant studies.\nThey identify a specific type of SVM classifier and con-\nclude that their method may be able to identify non-\nrandomised studies with a high degree of recall—as long\nas the citations on which the machine learning can\n\'train\' encapsulate the full range of the potentially rele-\nvant studies. Miwa et al. test explicitly the difference in\nperformance of the same machine learning approaches\nbetween \'clinical\' and \'social science\' reviews [45]. They\nfound that text mining performance was slightly poorer\nin the social scientific literature than the clinical domain\nand that certain enhancements could improve this.\nWallace and colleagues suggest a method to be used\nin review updates which enable reviewers to determine\nwhether a semi-automated approach is viable [48]. They\nrecommend a \'cross-fold validation\' test, whereby the\ndatabase of studies from the original review is split into\nparts (say, 10) and the classifier successively trained on\n90% of the data, leaving 10% for assessing its perform-\nance. Performance is then averaged over the 10 itera-\ntions and if acceptable, then the use of automation for\nthe update of that specific review can be recommended.\nFurther information on this topic\nMost text mining systems used in systematic reviews use\nshallow information e.g. bag-of-words and their combina-\ntions, e.g., kernels. Natural language processing techniques\nsuch as syntactic parsing can be employed to engineer\nmore discriminative features. Furthermore, unsupervised\nfeature learning or dimensionality reduction approaches\ncan be employed to build feature representations suitable\nfor specific domains as well as finding queries to relieve\nhasty generalisations as mentioned in 3.3.2 [82].\nOver-inclusive screeners\nThe success of most automated approaches relies upon\n\'gold standard\' training data; that is, citations that the\nmachine can assume have been correctly designated as\nrelevant or irrelevant. Using these data, the machine is\nthen able to build a model to designate such classifica-\ntions automatically. Usually, these gold standard training\ndata take the form of decisions made by reviewers when\nscreening a proportion of the studies of interest. Unfor-\ntunately, these decisions may not actually be \'gold stand-\nard\' training data, because reviewers are trained to be\nover inclusive, and to retrieve the full text whenever they\nare in doubt—even if the most likely final decision is\nthat it is irrelevant. Such decisions may mislead theclassifier and generate a model which incorrectly classi-\nfies irrelevant studies as relevant. Bekhuis et al. acknow-\nledge this as a potential problem, but go on to argue\nthen that to \'be worthwhile, a classifier must return per-\nformance better than this baseline to ensure reduced\nlabor\' [60]: a pragmatic way of looking at how machine\nlearning might potentially assist in systematic reviews.\nFrunza et al. also encountered this challenge, finding\nthat the best way of mitigating the effects of reviewer\nover-inclusivity was to base the machine learning on\ndesignations that were the result of two reviewers\' opin-\nions—after disagreements had been resolved [61]. This\nsolution is clearly only possible when two reviewers are\nreviewing every abstract—something which is common,\nbut by no means universal, practice.\nFurther information on this topic\nA machine learning-based method able to deal with\nover-inclusive screening as well as data imbalance is\ncost-sensitive learning [83]. Cost-sensitive learning as-\nsigns misclassification costs to certain types in learning\nand adapts machine-learning methods for task-specific\ncriteria. It is as competitive as or better than sampling\nmethods for unbalanced datasets [84], and it is also\nemployed in active learning [85].\nDiscussion\nSummary of key findings\nThis review asked five research questions, which we have\naddressed through synthesising the evidence from 44\nevaluations of the use of text mining for reducing\nscreening workload in systematic reviews.\nThe first research question related to the state of the\nevidence base, which we conclude to be both active and\ndiverse. The timeline indicates that the field is evolving\nrapidly, with new issues being tackled almost every year\nsince its application to systematic reviews. However,\nthis also hints at an issue that was elaborated on\nthroughout this paper—that is, there is almost no repli-\ncation between studies or collaboration between re-\nsearch teams, making it difficult to establish any overall\nconclusions about best approaches.\nThe second research question related to the purpose of\nusing text mining to reduce workload and the methods\nused for each purpose. For reducing the number needed to\nbe screened, it is reasonable to assume that the more inter-\nactive approach offered by a ranking or prioritisation sys-\ntem and the active learning approaches will have greater\nuser appeal than a strict classifier approach in \'new\' reviews\n(as opposed to review updates). This is because reviewers\nmight be uncomfortable with handing over too much con-\ntrol to an automated system. Also, when using a ranking or\nprioritisation approach, reviewers are able to search more\nsensitively than is currently the norm and screen the same\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 18 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5number of studies as they currently would; the effort spent\nscreening manually would thus be focused on those studies\nidentified as being themost relevant retrieved in the search,\nenabling these reviews to identify more relevant studies\nthan is currently the case.\nFor using text mining to replace a second human\nscreener, classifiers were used to make explicit in/out de-\ncisions and those decisions were compared with a hu-\nman reviewer. This approach is likely to have strong\nappeal amongst the systematic review community be-\ncause, whilst it reduces the resources required to screen\nitems, 100% of the items identified through searching\nare still viewed by a human screener. This could combat\nconcerns about false negatives assigned by an automated\nscreener. A further potential benefit of such a system is\nthat it \'could deliver quality assurance both by confirm-\ning concordant decisions and by naming studies associ-\nated with discordant decisions for further consideration\'\n(Bekhuis [60], p. 9) (One possible weakness of this ap-\nproach is that it necessarily assumes that any mistakes\nmade by the human screener are essentially at random,\nand not because of some systematic misapplication of\nthe inclusion criteria, which might be picked up and ad-\ndressed if two reviewers were working in tandem.).\nReducing workload by increasing the rate (or speed) of\nscreening was a little researched topic, exclusively lim-\nited to the visual data mining approach and largely\nchampioned by one research group. A major limitation\nof these evaluations—and potentially for the wider ap-\nplicability of these approaches—is that the approach has\nonly been tested on very small datasets. The largest data-\nset consisted of only 261 items to be screened [13]. It is\nunclear whether such an approach could be scaled up to\nbe applied in other disciplines in which thousands of\nitems might need to be screened, though the authors\nargue that upscaling is indeed possible. The efficient cit-\nation assignment approach evaluated by Wallace et al.\n[49] may also be promising for larger reviews where the\nexpertise of the reviewers is known.\nImproving workflow efficiency through screening pri-\noritisation is likely to appeal to systematic reviewers as it\nallows for reviewers to screen 100% of the titles and ab-\nstract but with a range of benefits. Benefits discussed in\nthe literature included: understanding the inclusion cri-\nteria sooner, getting up to speed on new developments\nin review updates, starting full-text document retrieval\nsooner and starting the data extraction and synthesis\nprocesses in parallel with screening the \'tail end\' of the\nlist of items (in which there are expected to be very few\nor zero relevant items).\nThe third research question related to the contextual\nproblems of applying text mining to systematic review\nscreening and how they have been addressed in the litera-\nture. We found various attempts to address theimportance of high recall for systematic reviews (vote\ncounting; specialist algorithms; and human input).\nWhilst all evaluations reported good recall, the studies\nused different adaptations; so it is impossible to conclude\nwhether any approach is better than another—and in\nwhich context. However, human input is likely to have\nintuitive appeal to systematic reviewers, as it allows for\na human sense-check of the terminology preferences\ndetermined by the machine.\nOne important distinction to make when evaluating\nthe utility of machine learning in screening is whether\none is creating a new review or updating and existing\none. Given the existence of the preexisting data for re-\nview updates, it is often possible to know in advance the\nlikely performance of using text mining, enabling re-\nviewers to make an informed decision about its potential\nin that specific review. Such a situation does not pertain\nin new reviews, and the risk of hasty generalisation is a\n\'known unknown\' here, as are the risks and benefits of\nadopting a semi-automated approach.\nThe lack of replication and testing outside the biomed-\nical sphere makes it difficult to draw conclusions about\nthe general effectiveness of these technologies. Certainly,\nwhere technical jargon is utilised, most approaches ap-\npear to offer efficiency savings; and in the few instances\nof their application outside the medical domain they\nagain can be effective, though potentially slightly less so.\nThe fourth research question considered how the\nworkload reduction issue has been evaluated. Here, it\nwas impossible to synthesise study findings quantita-\ntively, because each used different technologies in (usu-\nally) different reviews. On the whole, most suggested\nthat a saving in workload of between 30% and 70%\nmight be possible (with some a little higher or a little\nlower than this), though sometimes the saving in work-\nload is accompanied by the loss of 5% of relevant studies\n(i.e. a 95% recall).\nThe fifth research question considered the challenges\nto implementation that emerged from reviewing the evi-\ndence base. Here, we found few deployed systems, which\nlimits the ability of reviewers to try out these technolo-\ngies, but also, given the limitations in the evidence base\nidentified above, there is probably a need for specialist\nadvice whenever they are used in a live review—and cer-\ntainly if workload reduction is planned (i.e. if their use\nextends beyond prioritising screening). We also found a\nlack of replication studies, which makes it difficult to\ncompare the efficacy of different approaches across re-\nview contexts, and few evaluations outside the biomed-\nical domain. Challenges in using such technologies\ninclude questions about how they might scale to large\nreviews and how to model accurate classifiers when the\ndecisions made by reviewers are likely to err on the side\nof caution, and hence be over-inclusive.\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 19 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5Strengths and limitations of this review\nTo the best of our knowledge, this is the first systematic re-\nview that has brought together evidence concerning the use\nof text mining for screening in systematic reviews. We have\nidentified a varied, innovative and potentially extremely im-\nportant evidence base—which one day may do much to im-\nprove review efficiency and so improve decision-making.\nWe hope that this review will help the different areas of the\nfield to \'speak\' to one another and so facilitate the develop-\nment of the field as a whole.\nAs there are no other systematic reviews of this area, we\nhad a broad review question, which encompassed any ap-\nproach. This has enabled us to identify the cross-cutting\nissues in the field but has limited the quantity of technical\ninformation that we have been able to present. For ex-\nample, a narrower review focused solely on active learning\nmight be able to delve into the specifics in more detail.\nAn inevitable limitation due to setting the scope of the\nreview to evaluations of text mining approaches within\nsystematic reviews is that relevant research in other\nareas is excluded. For example, if we had reviewed all\npotentially relevant research about text mining and ac-\ntive learning (an almost impossible task!), other tech-\nnologies and approaches, beyond those so far evaluated in\nsystematic reviews, might well have come to light. Whilst\nthis limitation was impossible to avoid, it is nevertheless a\nsignificant limitation, because only a small subset of pos-\nsible approaches to, for example, feature selection/enrich-\nment and distance analytics, have been tested within the\nsystematic review literature. The field of text mining con-\ntains many more possibilities—and some may be more ef-\nfective and appropriate than those so far evaluated.\nA limitation which applies to any systematic review is\nthat we may not have managed to find every relevant\nstudy. This was highlighted to us during the peer review\nprocess when another relevant study came to light. This\nstudy was focused on a text mining approach and uti-\nlised data from systematic reviews as its test scenario\n[71]. There may be other papers like this one which we\nhave inadvertently missed.\nFurther possibilities\nIt is interesting to note that text mining approaches to\nsupport screening have followed the human reviewer\'s\ninitial approach of using titles, abstracts and keywords.\nThe human reviewer will retrieve full text for further re-\nview, but typically text mining approaches so far have\nnot processed full text in support of the screening\nprocess. There are essentially three issues to consider\nhere. Firstly, there is the issue of how well a title, ab-\nstract and metadata can satisfy a complex information\nneed. For example, regarding use of an abstract to deter-\nmine what claims are being made, Blake found that, in\nbiomedicine, fewer than 8% of the scientific claims madein full-text articles were to be found in their abstracts,\nwhich would certainly motivate the need to process full\ntext [86].\nCohen and colleagues have investigated more widely\nthe implications for text mining of processing abstracts\nas opposed to full-text articles, and moreover mention a\nsecond issue, to do with problems that may arise for sys-\ntems in going from the processing of abstracts to the\nprocessing of full text, but note that there are opportun-\nities to be exploited in so doing [87]. Text mining technol-\nogy has, however, improved greatly since that publication.\nThere are now text mining systems that process large\namounts of full text and that support sophisticated seman-\ntic search. For example, Europe PubMed Central, a large\narchive for the Life Sciences, showcases on its Labs site a\nsemantic search system, EvidenceFinder, that is under-\npinned by deep parsing, conducted in a cloud environ-\nment, of some 2.5 m articles to yield over 83 m searchable\nfacts (http://labs.europepmc.org/evf).\nText mining can increasingly handle deep analysis of\nfull-text context, at scale, thus it would be natural to\nmove towards exploiting such a capability in support of\nsystematic reviews. However, this leads into the third\nissue, concerning copyright, licencing and lawful access\nto full-text content for text mining purposes. Reviewers\nalready run into this issue when they find that their in-\nstitution does not subscribe to some journal, for ex-\nample. However, even if one\'s institution does have the\nrelevant subscription, licencing terms may explicitly dis-\nallow text mining or allow it but place constraints on\nuse of its results. This is a hot topic, with researchers\nclaiming that \'the right to read is the right to mine\'\n(Open Knowledge Foundation). Open Access publications\nare not subject to the same constraints as subscription-\nbased content; however, there is growing concern amongst\nresearchers and funding bodies that opportunities are be-\ning lost to advance knowledge and boost innovation and\ngrowth due to restrictive copyright and licencing regimes\nthat are unsuited to the digital age [88,89]. Most recently,\nthe UK has passed legislation to legalise text mining for\nnon-commercial use (http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/\n2014/1372/regulation/3/made). There is thus a valuable\nopportunity for the systematic reviewing community in\nthe UK at least to work closely with its text mining com-\nmunity to exploit the benefits of full-text processing, par-\nticularly to improve screening and to reduce the need for\nhumans to laboriously move from abstract to full text to\ncarry out a more specific check for relevance.\nThe use of automation to assist in study selection is pos-\nsibly the most advanced of all the areas where automation\nin systematic reviews is being developed; but others range\nfrom writing sections of the report, formulating the review\nquestion and automated data extraction and quality\nassessment [90-93].\nO\'Mara-Eves et al. Systematic Reviews 2015, 4:5 Page 20 of 22\nhttp://www.systematicreviewsjournal.com/content/4/1/5Recommendations\nRecommendations for research\n More replications using the same text mining\nmethods on different datasets are required.\n Likewise, different methods using the same dataset\nare also needed in order genuinely to compare\none with another.\n To facilitate the above, data on which evaluations\nare based should be made public as often\nas possible.\n The testing of the methods reviewed here in other\ndisciplines is urgently required. For example, the\nfield of Development Studies may be more\ncomplex and thus demand more of the text\nmining (promoting more innovation to overcome\nnew hurdles).\nRecommendations for reviewing practice\n Reviewers should engage with the computer science\ncommunity to develop and evaluate methods and\nsystems jointly.\n Using text mining to prioritise the order in which\nitems are screened should be considered safe and\nready for use in \'live\' reviews.\n The use of text mining as a \'second screener\' may be\nused cautiously in the knowledge that the\nassumption is that the human reviewer is not\nmissing relevant studies systematically.\n The use of text mining to eliminate studies\nautomatically should be considered promising,\nbut not yet fully proven. In highly technical/\nclinical areas, it may be used with a high degree\nof confidence; but more developmental and\nevaluative work is needed in other disciplines.Conclusion\nWhilst there is a relatively abundant and active evidence\nbase evaluating the use of text mining for reducing\nworkload in screening for systematic reviews, it is a di-\nverse and complex literature. The vast array of different\nissues explored makes it difficult to draw any conclu-\nsions about the most effective approach. There are, how-\never, key messages regarding the complexity of applying\ntext mining to the systematic review context and the\nchallenges that implementing such technologies in this\narea will encounter. Future research will particularly\nneed to address: the issue of replication of evaluations;\nthe suitability of the technologies for use across a range\nof subject-matter areas; and the usability and acceptabil-\nity of using these technologies amongst systematic re-\nview (non-computer scientist) audiences.Endnotes\naA \'method\', in the context of this review, is the applica-\ntion of a specific technology or a process within a system-\natic review. This is a somewhat broad definition which\nincludes, for example, both the use of a classifier to classify\ncitations as being relevant/irrelevant; and also the \'active\nlearning\' approach, which incorporates a classifier as part\nof its process. This broad definition reflects the practical\npurpose of this review—we are interested in approaches\nthat can be applied in systematic reviews, and these may\nbe individual tools, combinations of tools or processes for\nusing them.\nbThe practicalities of implementing text mining in live\nreviews are the subject of a current project by the EPPI-\nCentre and NaCTeM, which aims to address some of\nthese issues.
